# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: criticism-of-fast-food
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] Individuals who consume 17–21% of their daily calories from added sugar are reported to have a 38% higher risk of dying from cardiovascular disease compared to those who consume 8% of their daily calories from added sugar.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] In the United States, added sugars may include sucrose or high-fructose corn syrup, both primarily composed of about half glucose and half fructose.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] Other types of added sugar ingredients include beet and cane sugars, malt syrup, maple syrup, pancake syrup, fructose sweetener, liquid fructose, fruit juice concentrate, honey, and molasses.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] The most common types of foods containing added sugars are sweetened beverages, including most soft drinks, and also desserts and sweet snacks, which represent 20% of daily calorie consumption, twice the maximum limit recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] Based on a 2012 study on the use of caloric and noncaloric sweeteners in some 85,000 food and beverage products, 74% of the products contained added sugar.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] Sweetened beverages contain a syrup mixture of the monosaccharides glucose and fructose formed by hydrolytic saccharification of the disaccharide sucrose.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] The bioavailability of liquid carbohydrates is higher than in solid sugars, as characterized by sugar type and by the estimated rate of digestion.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] There is evidence for a positive and causal relationship between excessive intake of fruit juices and increased risk of some chronic metabolic diseases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] In tandem with the Food and Agriculture Organization, the WHO published a revised food pyramid that splits up the diet into more health-directed groups, recommending that a maximum of 10% of an individual's diet should come from free sugars.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] Sugar companies disputed the WHO report for suggesting that consumption of free sugars within the food pyramid should only amount to a daily maximum of 10%, and that there should be no minimum sugar intake.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] In 2015, the WHO published a new guideline on sugar intake for adults and children as a result of an extensive review of the available scientific evidence by a multidisciplinary group of experts.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] The guideline recommends that both adults and children reduce the intake of free sugars to less than 10% of total energy intake.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration revised its regulations for nutrition facts labelling, with the changes becoming mandatory by July 2018 in most cases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] Among other changes, the revision requires labelling of "added sugars", using a daily value of 50 grams or 200 calories per day for a 2,000 calorie diet.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] EFSA stated: "We underlined there are uncertainties about chronic disease risk for people whose consumption of added and free sugars is below 10% of their total energy intake".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] In 2018, the American Heart Association recommended daily intake of sugar for men is 9 teaspoons or 36 grams (1.3 oz) per day, and for women, six teaspoons or 25 grams (0.88 oz) per day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/added-sugar] Overconsumption of sugars in foods and beverages may increase the risk of several diseases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Previously treated as being hormonally inert, in recent years adipose tissue has been recognized as a major endocrine organ, as it produces hormones such as leptin, estrogen, resistin, and cytokines (especially TNFα).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In obesity, adipose tissue is implicated in the chronic release of pro-inflammatory markers known as adipokines, which are responsible for the development of metabolic syndrome—a constellation of diseases including type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease and atherosclerosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is derived from preadipocytes and its formation appears to be controlled in part by the adipose gene.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The two types of adipose tissue are white adipose tissue (WAT), which stores energy, and brown adipose tissue (BAT), which generates body heat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue—more specifically brown adipose tissue—was first identified by the Swiss naturalist Conrad Gessner in 1551.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In humans, adipose tissue is located beneath the skin (subcutaneous fat), around internal organs (visceral fat), in bone marrow (yellow bone marrow), intermuscular (muscular system), and in the breast (breast tissue).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is found in specific locations, which are referred to as *adipose depots*.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In addition to adipocytes, which comprise the highest percentage of cells within adipose tissue, other cell types are present, collectively termed stromal vascular fraction (SVF) of cells.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] SVF includes preadipocytes, fibroblasts, adipose tissue macrophages, and endothelial cells.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue contains many small blood vessels.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In the integumentary system, which includes the skin, it accumulates in the deepest level, the subcutaneous layer, providing insulation from heat and cold.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Around organs, it provides protective padding.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose depots in different parts of the body have different biochemical profiles.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Under normal conditions, it provides feedback for hunger and diet to the brain.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In an obese person, excess adipose tissue hanging downward from the abdomen is referred to as a panniculus.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] A panniculus complicates surgery of the morbidly obese individual.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] It may remain as a literal "apron of skin" if a severely obese person loses large amounts of fat (a common result of gastric bypass surgery).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Obesity is treated through exercises, diet, behavioral therapy, and liposuctions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Reconstructive surgery is one aspect of treatment.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat or abdominal fat (also known as organ fat or intra-abdominal fat) is located inside the abdominal cavity, packed between the organs (stomach, liver, intestines, kidneys, etc.).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is different from subcutaneous fat underneath the skin, and intramuscular fat interspersed in skeletal muscles.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Fat in the lower body, as in thighs and buttocks, is subcutaneous and is not consistently spaced tissue, whereas fat in the abdomen is mostly visceral and semi-fluid.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is composed of several adipose depots, including mesenteric, epididymal white adipose tissue (EWAT), and perirenal depots.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is often expressed in terms of its area in cm2 (VFA, visceral fat area).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] An excess of visceral fat is known as abdominal obesity, or "belly fat", in which the abdomen protrudes excessively.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] New developments such as the Body Volume Index (BVI) are specifically designed to measure abdominal volume and abdominal fat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Excess visceral fat is also linked to type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance, inflammatory diseases, and other obesity-related diseases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Likewise, the accumulation of neck fat (or cervical adipose tissue) has been shown to be associated with mortality.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Several studies have suggested that visceral fat can be predicted from simple anthropometric measures, and predicts mortality more accurately than body mass index or waist circumference.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Men are more likely to have fat stored in the abdomen due to sex hormone differences.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Estrogen (female sex hormone) causes fat to be stored in the buttocks, thighs, and hips in women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] When women reach menopause and the estrogen produced by the ovaries declines, fat migrates from the buttocks, hips and thighs to the waist; later fat is stored in the abdomen.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat can be caused by excess cortisol levels.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] At least 10 MET-hours per week of aerobic exercise leads to visceral fat reduction in those without metabolic-related disorders.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Resistance training and caloric restriction also reduce visceral fat, although their effect may not be cumulative.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Both exercise and hypocaloric diet cause loss of visceral fat, but exercise has a larger effect on visceral fat versus total fat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] High-intensity exercise is one way to effectively reduce total abdominal fat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] An energy-restricted diet combined with exercise will reduce total body fat and the ratio of visceral adipose tissue to subcutaneous adipose tissue, suggesting a preferential mobilization for visceral fat over subcutaneous fat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Epicardial adipose tissue (EAT) is a particular form of visceral fat deposited around the heart and found to be a metabolically active organ that generates various bioactive molecules, which might significantly affect cardiac function.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Marked component differences have been observed in comparing EAT with subcutaneous fat, suggesting a location-specific impact of stored fatty acids on adipocyte function and metabolism.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Most of the remaining nonvisceral fat is found just below the skin in a region called the hypodermis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] This subcutaneous fat is not related to many of the classic obesity-related pathologies, such as heart disease, cancer, and stroke, and some evidence even suggests it might be protective.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The typically female (or gynecoid) pattern of body fat distribution around the hips, thighs, and buttocks is subcutaneous fat, and therefore poses less of a health risk compared to visceral fat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Like all other fat organs, subcutaneous fat is an active part of the endocrine system, secreting the hormones leptin and resistin.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The relationship between the subcutaneous adipose layer and total body fat in a person is often modelled by using regression equations.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The most popular of these equations was formed by Durnin and Wormersley, who rigorously tested many types of skinfold, and, as a result, created two formulae to calculate the body density of both men and women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] These equations present an inverse correlation between skinfolds and body density—as the sum of skinfolds increases, the body density decreases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Factors such as sex, age, population size or other variables may make the equations invalid and unusable, and, as of 2012, Durnin and Wormersley's equations remain only estimates of a person's true level of fatness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Marrow fat, also known as marrow adipose tissue (MAT), is a poorly understood adipose depot that resides in the bone and is interspersed with hematopoietic cells as well as bony elements.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The adipocytes in this depot are derived from mesenchymal stem cells (MSC) which can give rise to fat cells, bone cells as well as other cell types.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The fact that MAT increases in the setting of calorie restriction/ anorexia is a feature that distinguishes this depot from other fat depots.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Exercise regulates MAT, decreasing MAT quantity and diminishing the size of marrow adipocytes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The exercise regulation of marrow fat suggests that it bears some physiologic similarity to other white adipose depots.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Moreover, increased MAT in obesity further suggests a similarity to white fat depots.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Ectopic fat is the storage of triglycerides in tissues other than adipose tissue, that are supposed to contain only small amounts of fat, such as the liver, skeletal muscle, heart, and pancreas.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] This can interfere with cellular functions and hence organ function and is associated with insulin resistance in type-2 diabetes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] It is stored in relatively high amounts around the organs of the abdominal cavity, but is not to be confused with visceral fat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The specific cause for the accumulation of ectopic fat is unknown.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The cause is likely a combination of genetic, environmental, and behavioral factors that are involved in excess energy intake and decreased physical activity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Substantial weight loss can reduce ectopic fat stores in all organs and this is associated with an improvement of the function of those organs.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In the latter case, non-invasive weight loss interventions like diet or exercise can decrease ectopic fat (particularly in heart and liver) in overweight or obese children and adults.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Free fatty acids (FFAs) are liberated from lipoproteins by lipoprotein lipase (LPL) and enter the adipocyte, where they are reassembled into triglycerides by esterifying them onto glycerol.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Human fat tissue contains from 61% to 94% lipids.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Lean and obese individuals tend towards the low and high ends of this range, respectively.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] There is a constant flux of FFAs entering and leaving adipose tissue.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The net direction of this flux is controlled by insulin and leptin—if insulin is elevated, then there is a net inward flux of FFA, and only when insulin is low can FFA leave adipose tissue.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Insulin secretion is stimulated by high blood sugar, which results from consuming carbohydrates.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In humans, lipolysis (hydrolysis of triglycerides into free fatty acids) is controlled through the balanced control of lipolytic B-adrenergic receptors and a2A-adrenergic receptor-mediated antilipolysis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Fat cells have an important physiological role in maintaining triglyceride and free fatty acid levels, as well as determining insulin resistance.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Abdominal fat has a different metabolic profile—being more prone to induce insulin resistance.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] This explains to a large degree why central obesity is a marker of impaired glucose tolerance and is an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease (even in the absence of diabetes mellitus and hypertension).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Recent advances in biotechnology have allowed for the harvesting of adult stem cells from adipose tissue, allowing stimulation of tissue regrowth using a patient's own cells.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In addition, adipose-derived stem cells from both human and animals reportedly can be efficiently reprogrammed into induced pluripotent stem cells without the need for feeder cells.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The use of a patient's own cells reduces the chance of tissue rejection and avoids ethical issues associated with the use of human embryonic stem cells.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] A growing body of evidence also suggests that different fat depots (i.e. abdominal, omental, pericardial) yield adipose-derived stem cells with different characteristics.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] These depot-dependent features include proliferation rate, immunophenotype, differentiation potential, gene expression, as well as sensitivity to hypoxic culture conditions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Oxygen levels seem to play an important role on the metabolism and in general the function of adipose-derived stem cells.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is a major peripheral source of aromatase in both males and females, contributing to the production of estradiol.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissues also secrete a type of cytokines (cell-to-cell signalling proteins) called adipokines (adipose cytokines), which play a role in obesity-associated complications.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Perivascular adipose tissue releases adipokines such as adiponectin that affect the contractile function of the vessels that they surround.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Brown fat or brown adipose tissue (BAT) is a specialized form of adipose tissue important for adaptive thermogenesis in humans and other mammals.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] BAT can generate heat by "uncoupling" the respiratory chain of oxidative phosphorylation within mitochondria through tissue-specific expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] BAT is primarily located around the neck and large blood vessels of the thorax, where it may effectively act in heat exchange.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] BAT is robustly activated upon cold exposure by the release of catecholamines from sympathetic nerves that results in UCP1 activation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Nearly half of the nerves present in adipose tissue are sensory neurons connected to the dorsal root ganglia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] BAT activation may also occur in response to overfeeding.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] UCP1 activity is stimulated by long chain fatty acids that are produced subsequent to β-adrenergic receptor activation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] UCP1 is proposed to function as a fatty acid proton symporter, although the exact mechanism has yet to be elucidated.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In contrast, UCP1 is inhibited by ATP, ADP, and GTP.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Attempts to simulate this process pharmacologically have so far been unsuccessful.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Techniques to manipulate the differentiation of "brown fat" could become a mechanism for weight loss therapy in the future, encouraging the growth of tissue with this specialized metabolism without inducing it in other organs.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] A review on the eventual therapeutic targeting of brown fat to treat human obesity was published by Samuelson and Vidal-Puig in 2020.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Until recently, brown adipose tissue in humans was thought to be primarily limited to infants, but new evidence has overturned that belief.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Metabolically active tissue with temperature responses similar to brown adipose was first reported in the neck and trunk of some human adults in 2007, and the presence of brown adipose in human adults was later verified histologically in the same anatomical regions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Browning of WAT, also referred to as "beiging", occurs when adipocytes within WAT depots develop features of BAT.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] **Beige adipocytes** take on a multilocular appearance (containing several lipid droplets) and increase expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In doing so, these normally energy-storing adipocytes become energy-releasing adipocytes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The calorie-burning capacity of brown and beige fat has been extensively studied as research efforts focus on therapies targeted to treat obesity and diabetes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The drug 2,4-dinitrophenol, which also acts as a chemical uncoupler similarly to UCP1, was used for weight loss in the 1930s.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] However, it was quickly discontinued when excessive dosing led to adverse side effects including hyperthermia and death. β3-adrenergic agonists, like CL316,243, have also been developed and tested in humans.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] However, the use of such drugs has proven largely unsuccessful due to several challenges, including varying species receptor specificity and poor oral bioavailability.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Cold is a primary regulator of BAT processes and induces WAT browning.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Browning in response to chronic cold exposure has been well documented and is a reversible process.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] A study in mice demonstrated that cold-induced browning can be completely reversed in 21 days, with measurable decreases in UCP1 seen within a 24-hour period.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] A study by Rosenwald et al. revealed that when the animals are re-exposed to a cold environment, the same adipocytes will adopt a beige phenotype, suggesting that beige adipocytes are retained.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Transcriptional regulators, as well as a growing number of other factors, regulate the induction of beige fat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Four regulators of transcription are central to WAT browning and serve as targets for many of the molecules known to influence this process.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] These include peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ), PRDM16, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator 1 alpha (PGC-1α), and Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The list of molecules that influence browning has grown in direct proportion to the popularity of this topic and is constantly evolving as more knowledge is acquired.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Among these molecules are irisin and fibroblast growth factor 21 (FGF21), which have been well-studied and are believed to be important regulators of browning.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Irisin is secreted from muscle in response to exercise and has been shown to increase browning by acting on beige preadipocytes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] FGF21, a hormone secreted mainly by the liver, has garnered a great deal of interest after being identified as a potent stimulator of glucose uptake and a browning regulator through its effects on PGC-1α.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] It is increased in BAT during cold exposure and is thought to aid in resistance to diet-induced obesity FGF21 may also be secreted in response to exercise and a low protein diet, although the latter has not been thoroughly investigated.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Data from these studies suggest that environmental factors like diet and exercise may be important mediators of browning.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In mice, it was found that beiging can occur through the production of methionine-enkephalin peptides by type 2 innate lymphoid cells in response to interleukin 33.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Due to the complex nature of adipose tissue and a growing list of browning regulatory molecules, great potential exists for the use of bioinformatics tools to improve study within this field.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Studies of WAT browning have greatly benefited from advances in these techniques, as beige fat is rapidly gaining popularity as a therapeutic target for the treatment of obesity and diabetes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] DNA microarray is a bioinformatics tool used to quantify expression levels of various genes simultaneously, and has been used extensively in the study of adipose tissue.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] One such study used microarray analysis in conjunction with Ingenuity IPA software to look at changes in WAT and BAT gene expression when mice were exposed to temperatures of 28 and 6 °C.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The most significantly up- and downregulated genes were then identified and used for analysis of differentially expressed pathways.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] It was discovered that many of the pathways upregulated in WAT after cold exposure are also highly expressed in BAT, such as oxidative phosphorylation, fatty acid metabolism, and pyruvate metabolism.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] This suggests that some of the adipocytes switched to a beige phenotype at 6 °C.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Mössenböck et al. also used microarray analysis to demonstrate that insulin deficiency inhibits the differentiation of beige adipocytes but does not disturb their capacity for browning.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] These two studies demonstrate the potential for the use of microarray in the study of WAT browning.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] RNA sequencing (RNA-Seq) is a powerful computational tool that allows for the quantification of RNA expression for all genes within a sample.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Incorporating RNA-Seq into browning studies is of great value, as it offers better specificity, sensitivity, and a more comprehensive overview of gene expression than other methods.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] RNA-Seq has been used in both human and mouse studies in an attempt characterize beige adipocytes according to their gene expression profiles and to identify potential therapeutic molecules that may induce the beige phenotype.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] One such study used RNA-Seq to compare gene expression profiles of WAT from wild-type (WT) mice and those overexpressing Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] WAT from the transgenic animals exhibited a brown fat gene program and had decreased WAT specific gene expression compared to the WT mice.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Thus, EBF2 has been identified as a potential therapeutic molecule to induce beiging.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Chromatin immunoprecipitation with sequencing (ChIP-seq) is a method used to identify protein binding sites on DNA and assess histone modifications.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] This tool has enabled examination of epigenetic regulation of browning and helps elucidate the mechanisms by which protein-DNA interactions stimulate the differentiation of beige adipocytes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Studies observing the chromatin landscapes of beige adipocytes have found that adipogenesis of these cells results from the formation of cell specific chromatin landscapes, which regulate the transcriptional program and, ultimately, control differentiation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Using ChIP-seq in conjunction with other tools, recent studies have identified over 30 transcriptional and epigenetic factors that influence beige adipocyte development.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The thrifty gene hypothesis (also called the famine hypothesis) states that in some populations the body would be more efficient at retaining fat in times of plenty, thereby endowing greater resistance to starvation in times of food scarcity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In 1995, Jeffrey Friedman, in his residency at the Rockefeller University, together with Rudolph Leibel, Douglas Coleman et al. discovered the protein leptin that the genetically obese mouse lacked.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Leptin is produced in the white adipose tissue and signals to the hypothalamus.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] When leptin levels drop, the body interprets this as a loss of energy, and hunger increases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Mice lacking this protein eat until they are four times their normal size.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Leptin, however, plays a different role in diet-induced obesity in rodents and humans.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Because adipocytes produce leptin, leptin levels are elevated in the obese.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] However, hunger remains, and—when leptin levels drop due to weight loss—hunger increases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The drop of leptin is better viewed as a starvation signal than the rise of leptin as a satiety signal.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] However, elevated leptin in obesity is known as leptin resistance.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The changes that occur in the hypothalamus to result in leptin resistance in obesity are currently the focus of obesity research.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Gene defects in the leptin gene (*ob*) are rare in human obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Others have been identified as genetically partially deficient in leptin, and, in these individuals, leptin levels on the low end of the normal range can predict obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Several mutations of genes involving the melanocortins (used in brain signaling associated with appetite) and their receptors have also been identified as causing obesity in a larger portion of the population than leptin mutations.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Different cell types within adipose tissue exhibit distinct DNA methylation patterns.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Mature adipocytes and adipose progenitor cells (ASPCs) show a high degree of hypomethylation, affecting more than 50% of their regulatory regions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] This hypomethylation is associated with the activation of genes involved in triglyceride synthesis, such as glycerol‑3‑phosphate acyltransferase 1 (GPAM).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In contrast, myeloid cells display approximately 73% hypermethylated regions, reflecting an epigenetic program opposite to that of the adipocytic lineage.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Overall, there is a direct relationship between DNA demethylation and gene expression, whereby highly expressed genes tend to exhibit low methylation levels.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] These epigenetic patterns contribute to defining the functional identity of the different cell types within subcutaneous adipose tissue (SAT).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue has a density of ~0.9 g/ml.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Thus, a person with more adipose tissue will float more easily than a person of the same weight with more muscular tissue, since muscular tissue has a density of 1.06 g/ml.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In addition to the visible changes in adipose tissue associated with obesity, recent research indicates that the risk of developing abdominal obesity and cardiometabolic alterations also depends on the 3D organization of the genome in subcutaneous adipose tissue.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Single‑cell epigenomic studies have shown that many genetic variants associated with abdominal fat distribution (measured as WHRadjBMI) are preferentially located in active genomic regions of adipocytes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] These regions display low levels of DNA methylation and belong to the so‑called A compartment, which is characterized by higher gene activity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] These findings suggest that adipocytes in subcutaneous adipose tissue play a key role in mediating the genetic risk associated with abdominal obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] A **body fat meter** is a tool used to measure the body fat to weight ratio in the human body.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Different meters use various methods to determine the ratio.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] They tend to under-read body fat percentage.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] In contrast with clinical tools like DXA and underwater weighing, one relatively inexpensive type of body fat meter uses the principle of bioelectrical impedance analysis (BIA) in order to determine an individual's body fat percentage.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] To achieve this, the meter passes a small, harmless, electric current through the body and measures the resistance, then uses information on the person's weight, height, age, and sex to calculate an approximate value for the person's body fat percentage.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The calculation measures the total volume of water in the body (lean tissue and muscle contain a higher percentage of water than fat), and estimates the percentage of fat based on this information.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] The result can fluctuate several percentage points depending on what has been eaten and how much water has been drunk before the analysis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] This method is quick and readily accessible, but imprecise.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/adipose-tissue] Alternative methods are: skin fold methods using calipers, underwater weighing, whole body air displacement plethysmography (ADP) and DXA.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] They are known for publishing guidelines on cardiovascular disease and prevention, standards on basic life support, advanced cardiac life support (ACLS), pediatric advanced life support (PALS), and in 2014 issued the first guidelines for preventing strokes in women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Heart Association is also known for operating a number of highly visible public service campaigns starting in the 1970s, and also operates several fundraising events.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Originally formed in Chicago in 1924, the American Heart Association is currently headquartered in Dallas, Texas.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] It was originally headquartered in New York City.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Heart Association is a national voluntary health agency.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The mission of the organization, updated in 2018, is "To be a relentless force for a world of longer, healthier lives." The organization's work can be divided into five key areas: research; heart and brain health; equitable health; advocacy; and professional education and development.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 1924, cardiologists Paul Dudley White, Hugh D.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Conner, formed the Association for the Prevention and Relief of Heart Disease as a professional society for doctors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 1949, the American Heart Association received $1.5 million (equivalent to $17–20 million today) from individual listeners of a nationwide radio contest.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The fundraiser, called *The Walking Man*, aired on the popular program *Truth or Consequences*, which was sponsored by Duz dishwashing liquid (a product of Procter & Gamble).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] More than two million letters were submitted by listeners, each averaging a donation of 70 cents.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The outpouring of support marked a major turning point for the Association, enabling it to fund scientific research and launch national public health initiatives.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Since 1949, it has funded over $6.1 billion in cardiovascular, cerebrovascular, and brain health research.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The organization, now known as the American Heart Association, consists of over 33 million volunteers who are dedicated to improving heart health and reducing deaths from cardiovascular diseases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In the 1950s and 1960s, the American Heart Association published several reports and guidelines focused on recommended lifestyles to improve cardiovascular health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 1956, the American Heart Association issued its first scientific statement on smoking and heart disease, noting evidence of a possible link between tobacco use and cardiovascular deaths.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The Surgeon General's Report on Smoking and Health, during the 1960s, later recorded that the AHA was among several medical organizations to publicly identify smoking as an important health hazard associated with heart and lung disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] By 1961, these findings had been strengthened, leading to the new 1961 American Heart Association recommendations: (1) Maintain a correct body weight, (2) Engage in moderate exercise, e.g., walking to aid in weight reduction, (3) Reduce intake of total fat, saturated fat, and cholesterol.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Increase intake of polyunsaturated fat, (4) Men with a strong family history of atherosclerosis should pay particular attention to diet modification, and (5) Dietary changes should be carried out under medical supervision.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] These recommendations continued to become more precise from 1957 to 1980, but there maintained "a general coherence among them".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 1966, research supported by the American Heart Association provided evidence linking high blood pressure to reduced life expectancy and increased complications such as heart enlargement and vascular damage.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The findings helped establish hypertension as a major risk factor for cardiovascular disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 1994, the *Chronicle of Philanthropy*, an industry publication, released the results of the largest study of charitable and non-profit organization popularity and credibility.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The study showed that the American Heart Association was ranked as the fifth "most popular charity/non-profit in America" of over 100 charities researched, with 95 percent of Americans over the age of 12 choosing the *Love* and *Like A lot* description categories.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 1998, the AHA created the American Stroke Association to help prevent strokes, improve treatments, and maximize recoveries.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2003, the two organizations created the Get With the Guidelines (GWTG)-Stroke program.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] It is a voluntary registry that hospitals can use to receive the latest scientific treatment guidelines.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The program also collects data on patient characteristics, hospital adherence to guidelines, and patient outcomes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2004 the American Heart Association launched the "**Go Red for Women**" campaign specifically targeting women, with information about risks and action they can take to protect their health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] All revenues from the local and national campaigns go to support awareness, research, education and community programs to benefit women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2008, the AHA recommended "hands only" CPR as an option for bystanders who want to help keep a cardiac arrest victim alive.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] This method removes the practice of performing rescue breaths and depends solely on chest compressions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] On November 30, 2009, the American Heart Association announced a new cardiac arrest awareness campaign called Be the Beat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The campaign has sought to use fun ways to teach 12- to 15-year-olds the basics of cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The AHA has also taught them how to use an automated external defibrillator [AED].
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2012, the AHA renewed its focus on hands-only CPR by carrying out a national campaign to educate more people on how to perform this method.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Jennifer Coolidge was a spokesperson for the campaign.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] It also carried out a campaign in 2012 to educate more people on how to carry out hands-only CPR.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The 2012 campaign, which began in New York City, had Jennifer Coolidge as the spokesperson.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2013, the American Heart Association issued a joint guideline recognizing obesity as a disease and recommending its treatment by weight loss.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2014, the American Heart Association issued its first guidelines for preventing strokes in women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Just as heart attack systems differ between men and women, men and women also face different stroke risks.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] For women, the guidelines for preventing strokes focus on factors such as birth control, pregnancy, and depression.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2015, the American Heart Association officially endorsed the Tobacco 21 campaign, urging local, state and national governments to raise the tobacco and nicotine sales age from 18 to 21.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2016, the American Heart Association, Verily Life Sciences, and AstraZeneca invested $75 million in the One Brave Idea program.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The money was awarded to institutions researching new biomarkers, such as genetic and molecular factors, that put individuals at risk for atherosclerosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] It was hoped that the research would help the AHA reach its goals of increasing cardiovascular health by 20% and reducing cardiovascular mortality by 20% by 2020.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In November 2017, the American Heart Association and the American College of Cardiology, along with nine other professional groups, issued new guidelines lowering the threshold for diagnosing high blood pressure from 140/90 mm Hg to 130/80 mm Hg.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The change, the first in fourteen years, was intended to help identify cardiovascular risks earlier and encourage intervention before medication is needed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The following year in 2018, the organizations jointly released updated cholesterol management guidelines recommending the use of coronary artery calcium (CAC) scoring by clinicians to determine proper management of plaque buildup.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2018, the American Heart Association and American College of Cardiology issued new guidelines for clinicians on the management of cholesterol as a way to reduce risk for heart attack and stroke.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Newly included in the guidelines is a recommendation to use the coronary artery calcium score if healthcare providers are having difficulty deciding if a patient could benefit from statin medications or should focus solely on lifestyle modifications.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The cholesterol guidelines were last updated in 2013.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2020 and 2021, the annual flagship meeting of the organization was held virtually owing to the COVID-19 pandemic and resumed as an in-person conference in 2022.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In June 2024, the American Heart Association celebrated its 100 year anniversary of its founding.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] With the official celebration of its founding, the association was recognized as the nation's oldest and largest voluntary organization dedicated to fighting heart disease and stroke.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The association held CPR training, where in many places the first hundred or so people to participate in the 5-minute training were given take-home CPR kits.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] A 2026 survey by the Annenberg Public Policy Center found that the American Heart Association was the most trusted source of public health information after respondents' own physicians.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Some of the American Heart Association's research, campaigns, and other work are included here.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Since 1949, the association has funded over $6.1 billion in cardiovascular, cerebrovascular, and brain health research.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The Go Red for Women campaign started in 2004 to raise awareness that women, and not only men, are vulnerable to heart disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Between 2016 and 2021, the American Heart Association invested $20 million in the Go Red for Women Strategically Focused Research Network.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The SFRN also received $52 million from the National Institutes of Health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2017, the Go Red National Leadership Council was started to engage female executives in the campaign.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Additional projects associated with the campaign include Research Goes Red and National Wear Red Day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] As of 2023, over 900,000 women have joined the campaign and receive updates on what they can do to improve their heart health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The campaign's social media channels had audiences of over 5.3 million in 2022.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Also in 2023, Miss America's Scholarship Foundation, a 501(c)(3), announced a 3-year commitment supporting the American Heart Association's women's initiative, Go Red for Women®.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] This initiative raises funds and awareness of women's heart health and brings fitness initiatives back to the national Miss America competition stage after the swimsuit portion was scrapped in 2018.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The "Be the Beat" challenge encourages people to learn CPR.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The CEO Roundtable was formed in 2013 and focuses on implementing evidence-based approaches to workplace health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2020, the CEOs of CVS Health, Walgreens Boots Alliance, and US Foods joined the association.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2023, there were almost 50 Fortune 100 CEOs in the association.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 1998, the association created the American Stroke Association to help prevent strokes, improve treatments, and maximize recoveries.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Heart Association announced in October 2024 a grant aimed at improving heart health in rural communities by funding initiatives that address healthcare access and education.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] This support is expected to enhance resources for the prevention and treatment of heart disease in underserved areas.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] This 2023 Spanish-language campaign works to raise awareness among Hispanic Americans about stroke symptoms.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Stroke Association has launched a new Spanish-language website, to educate Hispanic and Latino communities about stroke recognition, prevention, and recovery.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] This is a joint campaign from the American heart Association and the American Diabetes Association.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] It works to raise awareness about the connection between diabetes and heart disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The AHA reports that adults with diabetes are 2–4 times more likely to die from heart disease than adults without diabetes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Control." program is an evidence-based hypertension management program that encourages blood pressure self-monitoring.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2019 it was used by more than 315,000 people.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] This program was started in 2023 to "educate and prepare teens and adults to be confident to save life in a cardiac emergency." More than 350,000 people have out-of-hospital cardiac arrests each year, and this program wants to help improve their survival rate.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] As part of National Wear Red Day, Buffalo Bills NFL player Damar Hamlin joined the American Heart Association at the Empire State Building to raise awareness about heart health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Hamlin, who survived a cardiac arrest on the field during a January 2023 game versus the Cincinnati Bengals, shared his experience of how a direct hit caused his heart to stop and emphasized the importance of heart health and emergency response.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Joseph Puma highlighted that timely medical attention, including heart scans, can prevent life-threatening events, urging individuals to seek care if experiencing chest pain, shortness of breath, or other warning signs of heart issues.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In January 2025, Hamlin partnered with the American Heart Association to promote CPR and AED awareness through a PSA for the Nation of Lifesavers initiative.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In the campaign, Hamlin emphasized the importance of immediate CPR and AED use, which he credited with saving his life.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Life's Essential 8 (LE8) are cardiovascular health measurements shared by the AHA.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Previously the measurements were known as the LE7, but in 2022 the AHA added sleep health as an additional behavioral metric.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The other metrics look at body weight, blood pressure, cholesterol, blood sugar, smoking, physical activity, and diet.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Heart Association's 2024 Impact Goal states, "Every person deserves the opportunity for a full, healthy life.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The HSI scholarship program is for any students enrolled in public health and healthcare focused programs at 18 Hispanic-serving colleges and universities.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The program's goal is to increase representation in health-care.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Students in the program are paired with volunteer mentors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] They develop and present a research project that addresses basic, clinical, and educational science, receive a stipend, and participate in professional development workshops.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Students and researchers study the impact of cardiovascular disease in their community, learn the factors affecting vulnerable populations, and sample areas of scientific inquiry.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Students also receive financial stipends.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] HeartCorps is the American Heart Association's Public Health AmeriCorps program and is designed to drive equitable health in rural America.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] As of November 2022, twenty-six states participated in the program.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Heart Association supports legislation that creates smoke-free workplaces and public spaces.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Starting in 2014, the AHA called for regulations for e-cigarettes to prevent young people from becoming addicted to nicotine, referencing studies that suggest that e-cigarettes can be a gateway drug.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Heart Association supports the No Surprises Act, stating it will keep costs and premiums down and encourage more people to seek care from healthcare professionals.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2022, the American Heart Association, the Rockefeller Foundation, Kroger, and other partners announced a plan to build a national Food is Medicine Research Initiative to help provide concrete evidence that food-as-medicine programs improve health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In September 2023, the AHA partnered with the National Association of Chain Drug Stores, the American Cancer Society, the American Diabetes Association, and the Food is Medicine Institute at the Friedman School of Nutrition Science and Policy at Tufts University to launch *Nourish My Health*.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] It is a national public education campaign that promotes the protective health benefits of nutritious food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] You're the Cure is the national grassroots network of the American Heart Association.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2016, voters in San Francisco, Oakland, and Albany, California, approved ballot measures implementing a one-cent-per-ounce tax on sugar-sweetened beverages, while Boulder, Colorado, passed a similar tax at two cents per ounce.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Public health advocates, including the American Heart Association, supported the measures as tools to reduce obesity and related health issues.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Beverage Association opposed the taxes, arguing they are ineffective and burdensome to consumers, and emphasized industry efforts to reduce sugar content and promote healthier choices through education and product reformulation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2017, the American Heart Association called for improving diet quality among SNAP recipients, including restricting the purchase of sugary drinks with benefits.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Citing health risks and related cost savings, the proposal has gained support from some policymakers but faces opposition from retailers.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Potential changes may be addressed in the upcoming Farm Bill reauthorization.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Academy of Pediatrics and the American Heart Association released a joint statement urging policies to reduce children's consumption of sugary drinks, including taxes, marketing restrictions, and clearer labeling.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] They cited health risks such as obesity and diabetes, while the American Beverage Association opposed the proposals, highlighting industry efforts to reduce sugar and promote consumer choice.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2024, in Santa Cruz, California, beverage industry companies spent $1.2 million opposing Measure Z, a local tax on sugary drink distributors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] While the industry cites a 2018 state law banning such taxes, experts argue the tax is legal and that the ban may be unconstitutional.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Measure Z aims to reduce sugary drink consumption and fund community programs, reflecting similar efforts in other California cities.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Supporters see it as a way to restore local control and limit industry influence on public health policies.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In May 2025, Santa Cruz implemented a voter-approved tax of 2 cents per ounce on sugar-sweetened beverages, becoming the first California city to enact such a measure since a statewide moratorium on new local soda taxes was established in 2018.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The measure was supported by the American Heart Association, which cited public health concerns and praised the city's efforts to counteract what it described as misinformation campaigns by the beverage industry.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The American Heart Association publishes healthcare guidelines, statements, and performance measures.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The AHA also holds an annual Scientific Sessions meeting, which covers several days and a number of medical/healthcare topics; and hosts an International Stroke Conference.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The Second Century of Science Initiative was announced in 2023 as part of the AHA's plans to celebrate its first 100 years.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Under the Initiative, the AHA awarded $20 million in grants to over 100 scientists in the U.S.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In 2003, the AHA and the American Stroke Association created the Get With the Guidelines (GWTG)-Stroke program.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Fellowship is open to wide-ranged medical professionals (physicians, scientists, etc.) who demonstrate a major and productive interest in cardiovascular diseases and stroke.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] The association has 16 different councils.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Members (at the Premium Professional or Premium Professional Plus level) of one of these councils can apply for Fellowship.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] All applicants from all councils will be evaluated against the same criteria.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Fellows are entitled to use the post-nominal designation FAmerican Heart Association (Fellow of the American Heart Association), which reflects not only the professional stature of the Fellow but also their record of valuable service to the association and the council.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] In addition, American Heart Association fellowship offers several benefits; e.g., reduced subscription rates for all American Heart Association print journals and reduced registration fees for American Heart Association Scientific Sessions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Nancy Brown has been the CEO of the American Heart Association since 2009.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Churchwell served a one-year term as the volunteer president from July 1, 2024, until June 30, 2025.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/american-heart-association] Rosen is the current volunteer president for American Heart Association, with her term starting on July 1, 2025, running until June 30, 2026.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Individuals with anorexia nervosa have a fear of gaining weight, despite the fact that they are typically underweight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The DSM-5 describes this perceptual symptom as "disturbance in the way in which one's body weight or shape is experienced".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Recent research has shown, that this disturbance is not based on a visual body size overestimation, rather than body dissatisfaction: individuals with anorexia can accurately visually identify their body size, but find severely underweight bodies the most attractive.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Individuals with anorexia nervosa may also deny that their symptoms or behaviors are indicative of illness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] They may weigh themselves frequently, eat small amounts, and only eat certain foods in order to be in as much control of their body appearance as possible.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Some patients with anorexia nervosa binge eat and purge to further influence their weight or shape.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Purging can manifest as induced vomiting, excessive exercise, and/or laxative abuse.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa has the highest mortality rate of any psychiatric diagnosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Medical complications may include osteoporosis, infertility, and heart damage, along with the cessation of menstrual periods and death.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Complications in men may include lowered testosterone.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In cases where the patients with anorexia nervosa continually refuse significant dietary intake and weight restoration interventions, a psychiatrist can declare the patient to lack capacity to make decisions, which results in a medical decision to be fed by restraint via nasogastric tube.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia often develops during adolescence or young adulthood.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The causes of anorexia nervosa are complex and vary across individuals, many of which can include genetic, societal, physiological, and environmental causes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Most commonly, the exacerbation of the mental illness is thought to follow a major life-change or stress-inducing events.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] There is strong evidence, however, that anorexia nervosa also has a genetic component, with identical twins being affected more often than fraternal twins, which sees a large number of genetic risk factors underlying the disorder: similar to other psychiatric disorders with genetic components.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Cultural factors also play a very significant role, with societies that value thinness having higher rates of the disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa also commonly occurs in athletes who play sports where a low bodyweight is thought to be advantageous for aesthetics or performance, such as dance, cheerleading, gymnastics, running, figure skating and ski jumping (*anorexia athletica*).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A daily low dose of olanzapine has been shown to increase appetite and assist with weight gain in anorexia nervosa patients.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Psychiatrists may prescribe patients with anorexia nervosa forms of medication to better manage anxiety or depression, these being disorders often commonly associated with the disorder.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] However, medications are not considered a cure for anorexia nervosa: such pathways rather address underlying causes for the disorder, which often assist in recovery of it by allowing the individual to have a clearer and healthier mental state to understand the complications of anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] It does not assist those who do not have any other related mental conditions that affect their ability to do so.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] It has been proven to assist in the recovery of other eating disorders, such as bulimia nervosa and binge eating disorder.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In severe cases, individuals may require to be fed by nasogastric tube to restore weight and healthy nutritional levels by force.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Evidence for benefit from nasogastric tube feeding is unclear; some individuals recover after the first incident of admission, while others have recurring treatments over many years: sometimes indefinitely.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The largest risk of relapse occurs within the first year post-discharge from eating disorder therapy treatment.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Within the first two years post-discharge, approximately 31% of anorexia nervosa patients relapse.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Many complications, both physical and psychological, improve or resolve with nutritional rehabilitation and adequate weight gain.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa is estimated to occur in approximately 0.3% to 4.3% of women and 0.2% to 1% of men in Western countries at some point in their life.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Levels in other countries are unclear due to undiagnosis and a lack of awareness, though it can be presumed it is more present in Western societies due to a higher focus on low body weight and beauty on social media and real life.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] There is an observation for an increase in the diagnosis of anorexia from the 20th century onwards: it is unclear whether this is due to an actual increase in its frequency or simply due to improved diagnostic capabilities.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In 2013, it directly resulted in about 600 deaths globally, up from 400 deaths in 1990.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Eating disorders also increase a person's risk of death from a wide range of other causes, including suicide.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] About 5% of people with anorexia die from complications over a ten-year period with medical complications and suicide being the primary and secondary causes of death respectively.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia has one of the highest death rates among mental illnesses, second only to opioid overdoses.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa is an eating disorder characterized by attempts to lose weight by way of starvation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A person with anorexia nervosa may exhibit a number of signs and symptoms, the type and severity of which may vary and be present but not readily apparent.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Although anorexia is often recognized by the physical signs, it is a mental disorder that can occur at any body weight: in the case where BMI remains at a healthy amount in adults, atypical anorexia nervosa is diagnosed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa, and the associated malnutrition that results from the self-imposed starvation, causes complications in every major organ system in the body.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] It can cause permanent changes in the brain due to a lack of essential nutrients in the body.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Hypokalemia, a drop in the level of potassium in the blood, is a sign of anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A significant drop in potassium can cause abnormal heart rhythms, constipation, fatigue, muscle damage, and paralysis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Interoception involves the conscious and unconscious sense of the internal state of the body, having an important role in homeostasis and regulation of emotions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Aside from noticeable physiological dysfunction, interoceptive deficits also prompt individuals with anorexia to concentrate on distorted perceptions of multiple elements of their body image.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] This exists in both people with anorexia and in healthy individuals due to impairment in interoceptive sensitivity and interoceptive awareness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Aside from weight gain and outer appearance, people with anorexia also report abnormal bodily functions such as indistinct feelings of fullness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] This is due to miscommunication between internal signals of the body and the brain.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Due to impaired interoceptive sensitivity, powerful cues of fullness may be detected prematurely in highly sensitive individuals, which add to decreased calorie consumption and generate anxiety surrounding food intake in anorexia patients.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] People with anorexia also report difficulty identifying and describing their emotional feelings and the inability to distinguish emotions from bodily sensations in general, called alexithymia: again, likely due to the miscommunication of signals within the body.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Interoceptive awareness and emotion are deeply intertwined.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia patients also exhibit emotional regulation difficulties that ignite emotionally cued eating behaviors, such as restricting food or excessive exercising.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Impaired interoceptive sensitivity and interoceptive awareness can lead anorexia patients to adapt distorted interpretations of weight gain that are cued by physical sensations related to digestion (e.g. fullness).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Combined, these interoceptive and emotional elements could together trigger maladaptive and negatively reinforced behavioral responses that assist in the maintenance of anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In addition to metacognition, people with anorexia also have difficulty with social cognition including interpreting others' emotions, and demonstrating empathy.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Abnormal interoceptive awareness and interoceptive sensitivity shown through all of these examples have been observed so frequently in anorexia that they have become key characteristics of the illness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Other psychological issues may factor into anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Some pre-existing disorders can increase a person's likelihood to develop an eating disorder.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Additionally, anorexia nervosa can contribute to the development of certain conditions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The presence of psychiatric comorbidity has been shown to affect the severity and type of anorexia nervosa symptoms in both adolescents and adults.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Post-traumatic stress disorder remains highly prevalent among patients with anorexia nervosa, with more comorbid PTSD being associated with more severe eating disorder symptoms.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Obsessive–compulsive disorder (OCD) and obsessive–compulsive personality disorder (OCPD) are highly comorbid with AN.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] OCD is linked with more severe symptomatology and worse prognosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The causality between personality disorders and eating disorders has yet to be fully established.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Other comorbid conditions include depression, alcoholism, substance abuse, borderline and other personality disorders, anxiety disorders, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, and body dysmorphic disorder (BDD).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Depression and anxiety are the most common comorbidities, and depression is associated with a worse outcome.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Autism spectrum disorder occurs more commonly among people with eating disorders than in the general population, with about 30% of children and adults with AN likely having autism.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Zucker *et al.* (2007) proposed that conditions on the autism spectrum make up the cognitive endophenotype underlying anorexia nervosa and appealed for increased interdisciplinary collaboration.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] There is evidence for biological, psychological, developmental, and sociocultural risk factors, but the exact cause of eating disorders is unknown.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Twin studies have shown a heritability rate of 28–58%.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] First-degree relatives of those with anorexia have roughly 12 times the risk of developing anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Association studies have been performed, studying 128 different polymorphisms related to 43 genes including genes involved in regulation of eating behavior, motivation and reward mechanics, personality traits and emotion.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Consistent associations have been identified for polymorphisms associated with agouti-related peptide, brain derived neurotrophic factor, catechol-o-methyl transferase, SK3 and opioid receptor delta-1.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Epigenetic modifications, such as DNA methylation, may contribute to the development or maintenance of anorexia nervosa, though clinical research in this area is in its infancy.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A 2019 study found a genetic relationship with mental disorders, such as schizophrenia, obsessive–compulsive disorder, anxiety disorder and depression; and metabolic functioning with a negative correlation with fat mass, type 2 diabetes and leptin.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Both prenatal and perinatal obstetric complications may factor into the development of anorexia nervosa, such as preterm birth, maternal anemia, diabetes mellitus, preeclampsia, placental infarction, and neonatal heart abnormalities.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Neonatal complications may also have an influence on harm avoidance, one of the personality traits associated with the development of AN.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Neuroendocrine dysregulation: altered signaling of peptides that facilitate communication between the gut, brain and adipose tissue, such as ghrelin, leptin, neuropeptide Y and orexin, may contribute to the pathogenesis of anorexia nervosa by disrupting regulation of hunger and satiety.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Gastrointestinal diseases: people with gastrointestinal disorders may be more at risk of developing disorders of eating practices than the general population, principally restrictive eating disturbances.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] An association of anorexia nervosa with celiac disease has been found.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Individuals with good dietary management may develop anxiety, food aversion and eating disorders because of concerns around cross contamination of their foods.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] With routinely asking celiac patients about weight or body shape concerns, dieting or vomiting for weight control, to evaluate the possible presence of an eating disorders, especially in women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa is more likely to occur in a person's pubertal years.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Studies have hypothesized that disordered eating patterns may also arise secondary to starvation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The results of the Minnesota Starvation Experiment, for example, showed that normal controls will exhibit many of the same behavioral patterns associated with AN when subjected to starvation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Similarly, scientific experiments conducted using mice have suggested that other mammals exhibit these same behaviors, especially compulsive movement, when caloric restriction is induced, likely mediated by various changes in the neuroendocrine system.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] This has given further rise to the hypothesis that anorexia nervosa and other restrictive eating disorders may be an evolutionarily advantageous adaptive response to a perceived famine in the environment.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Recent research has further expanded this perspective, showing how caloric restriction may be adaptive in volatile or uncertain environment - thus potentially explaining the association between an increased risk to develop anorexia nervosa and adverse childhood experiences.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Early theories of the cause of anorexia linked it to childhood sexual abuse or dysfunctional families; evidence is conflicting, and well-designed research is needed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The fear of food is known as *sitiophobia* or *cibophobia*, and is part of the differential diagnosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Other psychological causes of anorexia include low self-esteem, feeling as if there is lack of control, depression, anxiety, and loneliness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] People with anorexia are, in general, highly perfectionistic and most have obsessive compulsive personality traits which may facilitate sticking to a restricted diet.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] It has been suggested that patients with anorexia are rigid in their thought patterns, and place a high level of importance upon being thin.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In the context of anorexia nervosa, this cognitive rigidity refers to the diminished ability to adapt one's behavioral approaches in response to changing circumstances.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] This weaker cognitive flexibility is a result of neurobiological factors, such as structural differences in prefrontal cortex connectivity, that contribute to the persistence of anorexic behaviors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Although the prevalence rates vary greatly, between 37% and 100%, there appears to be an association between traumatic events and eating disorder diagnosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Approximately 72% of individuals with anorexia report experiencing a traumatic event prior to the onset of eating disorder symptoms, with binge-purge subtype reporting the highest rates.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] There are many traumatic events that have been identified as possible risk factors for the development of anorexia, the first of which was childhood sexual abuse.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The prevalence of post-traumatic stress disorder among anorexia nervosa patients ranges from 4% to 24%.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A complicated symptom profile develops when trauma and anorexia meld; the bodily experience of the individual is changed and intrusive thoughts and sensations may be experienced.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Traumatic events can lead to intrusive and obsessive thoughts, and the symptom of anorexia that has been most closely linked to a PTSD diagnosis is increased obsessive thoughts pertaining to food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Similarly, impulsivity is linked to the purge and binge-purge subtypes of anorexia, trauma, and PTSD.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Emotional trauma (e.g., invalidation, chaotic family environment in childhood) may lead to difficulty with emotions, particularly the identification of and how physical sensations contribute to the emotional response.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] When trauma is perpetrated on an individual, it can lead to feelings of not being safe within their own body.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Both physical and sexual abuse can lead to an individual seeing their body as belonging to an "other" and not to the "self".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Individuals who feel as though they have no control over their bodies due to trauma may use food as a means of control because the choice to eat is an unmatched expression of control.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] By controlling the intake of food, individuals can decide when and how much they eat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Individuals, particularly children experiencing abuse, may feel a loss of control over their life, circumstances, and their own bodies.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Particularly sexual abuse, but also physical abuse, can make individuals feel that the body is not a safe place and an object over which another has control.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Starvation, in the case of anorexia, may also lead to reduction in the body as a sexual object, making starvation a solution.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Restriction may also be a means by which the pain an individual is experiencing can be communicated.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa has been increasingly diagnosed since 1950; the increase has been linked to vulnerability and internalization of body ideals.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] People in professions where there is a particular social pressure to be thin (such as models and dancers) were more likely to develop anorexia, and those with anorexia have much higher contact with cultural sources that promote weight loss.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Internet usage heavily leads to deep societal practices of the upkeep of slender body types.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Thus leading many to have symptoms of body dissatisfaction and low body image satisfaction.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] This trend can also be observed for people who partake in certain sports, such as jockeys and wrestlers.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] There is a higher incidence and prevalence of anorexia nervosa in sports with an emphasis on aesthetics, where low body fat is advantageous, and sports in which one has to make weight for competition.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Family group dynamics can play a role in the perpetuation of anorexia including negative expressed emotion in overprotective families where blame is frequently experienced among its members.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In the face of constant pressure to be thin, often perpetuated by teasing and bullying, feelings of low self-esteem and self-worth can arise, including the perception that one is not "deserving" of food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Persistent exposure to media that presents thin ideals may constitute a risk factor for body dysmorphia, leading to the development of anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Western cultures that favor thin bodies as the beauty standard often have higher rates of anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Media sources such as magazines, television shows, and social media can contribute to body dissatisfaction and disordered eating globally, by emphasizing slimness rooted in Western ideals.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Among magazines popular with people aged 18 to 24, those with a predominantly male audience were more likely to feature advertisements and articles focused on body shape in relation to body culture rather than promoting healthy diet.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In addition to the direct effect of media on female body perception, media indirectly affects female body image through giving men a false perception of what a female body is meant to look like.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Body dissatisfaction and internalization of body ideals are risk factors for anorexia nervosa that threaten the health of both male and female populations, with a predominant focus on women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Another online aspect contributing to higher rates of eating disorders such as anorexia nervosa are websites and communities on social media that stress the importance attaining the "ideal" body.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] These communities promote anorexia nervosa through the use of religious metaphors, lifestyle demonstrations, and photo galleries or quotes meant to motivate the individual's pursuit of thinness (commonly referred to as "thinspiration," "bone-spiration," and "fitspiration").
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] These pro-anorexia websites reinforce internalization of body ideals and the importance of their attainment.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Cultural attitudes towards body image, beauty, and health also significantly impact the incidence of anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] There is a stark contrast between Western societies that idolize slimness and certain Eastern traditions that worship gods depicted with larger bodies, and these varying cultural norms have varying influences on eating behaviors, self-perception, and anorexia in their respective cultures.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] For example, despite the fact that "fat phobia", or a fear of fat, is a key diagnostic criteria of anorexia by the DSM-5, anorexic patients in Asia rarely display this trait, as deep-rooted cultural values in Asian cultures praise larger bodies.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Fat phobia appears to be intricately linked to Western culture, encompassing how various cultural perceptions impact anorexia in various ways.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] It calls on the need for greater, diverse cultural consideration when looking at the diagnosis and experience of anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] For instance, in a cross-sectional study done on British South Asian adolescent English adolescent anorexia patients, it was found that both patients' symptom profiles differed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] South Asians were less likely to exhibit fat-phobia as a symptom versus their English counterparts, instead exhibiting loss of appetite.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Patients usually attributed their restricted food intake to somatic symptoms such as bloating, stomach pain, or lack of appetite.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] However, both kinds of patients had distorted body images, implying the possibility of disordered eating and highlighting the need for cultural sensitivity when diagnosing anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Collectivist and individualistic values also play a role in the manifestation of symptoms.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Patients in China are more likely to display denial or minimization of symptoms since they are culturally encouraged to use conceal their symptoms to preserve group harmony.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] These cultural differences are further empathized in research on the Caribbean island of Curaçao which revealed a substantially lower overall incidence of anorexia nervosa than that observed in the United States and Western Europe.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Specifically, no cases were identified among the majority Black population, while the minority mixed and white population showed incidence rates similar to those in Western countries.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] This disparity highlights potential cultural variations in the development and presentation of anorexia nervosa, particularly when comparing Black women in Curaçao to those exposed to Western cultural influences.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Notably, although these cultural distinctions persist, modernization and globalization slowly homogenize these attitudes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia is increasingly tied to the pressures of a global culture that celebrates Western ideals of thinness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The spread of Western media, fashion, and lifestyle ideals across the globe has begun to shift perceptions and standards of beauty in diverse cultures, contributing to a rise in the incidence of anorexia in places they were once rare.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia, once primarily associated with Western culture, seems more than ever to be linked to the cultures of modernity and globalization.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] However, unique cultural-specific phenotypes of disordered eating emerged prior to Western influence.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] For example, restrictive eating patterns were found in Japan as early as the 18th century and fewer reports of eating disorders were found between 1868 and 1944, when rapid Westernization occurred.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Sex-specific stressors and cultural dynamics could be implicated in this independent development of anorexia nervosa symptomology.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Evidence from physiological, pharmacological and neuroimaging studies suggest serotonin (also called 5-HT) may play a role in anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] While acutely ill, metabolic changes may produce a number of biological findings in people with anorexia that are not necessarily causative of the anorexic behavior.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] For example, abnormal hormonal responses to challenges with serotonergic agents have been observed during acute illness, but not recovery.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Nevertheless, increased cerebrospinal fluid concentrations of 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid (a metabolite of serotonin), and changes in anorectic behavior in response to acute tryptophan depletion (tryptophan is a metabolic precursor to serotonin) support a role in anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The activity of the 5-HT2A receptors has been reported to be lower in patients with anorexia in a number of cortical regions, evidenced by lower binding potential of this receptor as measured by PET or SPECT, independent of the state of illness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] While these findings may be confounded by comorbid psychiatric disorders, taken as a whole they indicate serotonin in anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] These alterations in serotonin have been linked to traits characteristic of anorexia such as obsessiveness, anxiety, and appetite dysregulation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Neuroimaging studies investigating the functional connectivity between brain regions have observed a number of alterations in networks related to cognitive control, introspection, and sensory function.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Alterations in networks related to the dorsal anterior cingulate cortex may be related to excessive cognitive control of eating related behaviors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Similarly, altered somatosensory integration and introspection may relate to abnormal body image.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A review of functional neuroimaging studies reported reduced activations in "bottom up" limbic region and increased activations in "top down" cortical regions which may play a role in restrictive eating.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Compared to controls, people who have recovered from anorexia show reduced activation in the reward system in response to food, and reduced correlation between self reported liking of a sugary drink and activity in the striatum and anterior cingulate cortex.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Increased binding potential of 11C radiolabelled raclopride in the striatum, interpreted as reflecting decreased endogenous dopamine due to competitive displacement, has also been observed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Structural neuroimaging studies have found global reductions in both gray matter and white matter, as well as increased cerebrospinal fluid volumes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Regional decreases in the left hypothalamus, left inferior parietal lobe, right lentiform nucleus and right caudate have also been reported in acutely ill patients.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] However, these alterations seem to be associated with acute malnutrition and largely reversible with weight restoration, at least in nonchronic cases in younger people.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In contrast, some studies have reported increased orbitofrontal cortex volume in currently ill and in recovered patients, although findings are inconsistent.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Reduced white matter integrity in the fornix has also been reported.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A diagnostic assessment includes the person's current circumstances, biographical history, current symptoms, and family history.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The assessment also includes a mental state examination, which is an assessment of the person's current mood and thought content, focusing on views on weight and patterns of eating.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa is classified under the Feeding and Eating Disorders in the fifth revision of the *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders* (DSM-5).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] There is no specific BMI cut-off that defines low weight required for the diagnosis of anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Relative to the previous version of the DSM (DSM-IV-TR), the 2013 revision (DSM-5) reflects changes in the criteria for anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Most notably, the amenorrhea (absent period) criterion was removed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Amenorrhea was removed for several reasons: it does not apply to males, it is not applicable for females before the age of menstruation, during or after the menopause, or women of any age taking birth control.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Additionally, some women who meet the other criteria for AN still report some menstrual activity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The use of the body mass index in the diagnosis of eating disorders has been controversial, largely owing to its oversimplification of health and failure to take into account complicating factors such as body composition or the initial bodyweight of the patient prior to the onset of AN.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Anorexia nervosa is classified under feeding or eating disorders in both the ICD-11 and the DSM-5.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Like the DSM-5, the ICD-11 also distinguishes between a binge-purge pattern and a restricting pattern with further subcodes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Terminal anorexia nervosa (TAN) is a proposed psychiatric diagnosis and is not currently clinically recognized.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] It may be used to facilitate access to medical assistance in dying (MAID).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Patients may be considered for TAN if they are at least 30 years old, have previously and persistently received "high-quality multidisciplinary eating disorder care," and have clearly and consistently expressed that additional treatment would be futile.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Medical tests to check for signs of physical deterioration in anorexia nervosa may be performed by a general physician or psychiatrist.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A variety of medical and psychological conditions have been misdiagnosed as anorexia nervosa; in some cases the correct diagnosis was not made for more than ten years.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] The distinction between binge purging anorexia, bulimia nervosa and Other Specified Feeding or Eating Disorders (OSFED) is often difficult for non-specialist clinicians.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] A main factor differentiating binge-purge anorexia from bulimia is the gap in physical weight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Patients with bulimia nervosa are ordinarily at a healthy weight, or slightly overweight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Patients with binge-purge anorexia are commonly underweight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] Moreover, patients with the binge-purging subtype may be significantly underweight and typically do not binge-eat large amounts of food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] In contrast, those with bulimia nervosa tend to binge large amounts of food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p01] It is not unusual for patients with an eating disorder to "move through" various diagnoses as their behavior and beliefs change over time.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Treatment for people with anorexia nervosa should be individualized and tailored to each person's medical, psychological, and nutritional circumstances.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Treating this condition with an interdisciplinary team is suggested so that the different health care professional specialties can help addresses the different challenges that can be associated with recovery.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Treatment for anorexia typically involves a combination of medical, psychological interventions such as therapy, and nutritional interventions (diet).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Hospitalization may also be needed in some cases, and the person requires a comprehensive medical assessment to help direct the treatment options.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] There is no conclusive evidence that any particular treatment approach for anorexia nervosa works better than others.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In some clinical settings a specific body image intervention is performed to reduce body dissatisfaction and body image disturbance.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Although restoring the person's weight is the primary task at hand, optimal treatment also includes and monitors behavioral change in the individual as well.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Psychological support, often in the form of cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT), family-based treatment, or psychotherapy aims to change distorted thoughts and behaviors around food, body image, and self-worth, with family-based therapy also being a key approach for younger patients.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Family-based treatment (FBT) may be more successful than individual therapy for adolescents with AN.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Proponents of family therapy for adolescents with AN assert that it is important to include parents in the adolescent's treatment.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The evidence supporting family based therapy for adults is weak and despite the evidence that it is effective and the primary choice for treatment in adolescents, there is no evidence it is helpful for adults.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] A four- to five-year follow up study of the Maudsley family therapy, an evidence-based manualized model, showed full recovery at rates up to 90%.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The Maudsley model of family therapy is problem focused, and the treatment targets re-establishing regular eating, weight restoration, and the reduction of illness behaviors like purging.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Although this model is recommended by the National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH), critics claim that it has the potential to create power struggles in an intimate relationship and may disrupt equal partnerships.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) is useful in adolescents and adults with anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] One of the most known psychotherapy in the field is CBT-E, an enhanced cognitive-behavior therapy specifically focus to eating disorder psychopathology.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Acceptance and commitment therapy is a third-wave cognitive-behavioral therapy which has shown promise in the treatment of AN.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Cognitive remediation therapy (CRT) is also used in treating anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Schema-Focused Therapy (a form of CBT) was developed by Dr.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Jeffrey Young and is effective in helping patients identify origins and triggers for disordered eating.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Psychotherapy for individuals with AN is challenging as they may value being thin and may seek to maintain control and resist change.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Initially, developing a desire to change is fundamental.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] There is no strong evidence to suggest one type of psychotherapy over another for treating anorexia nervosa in adults or adolescents.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Diet is the most essential factor to work on in people with anorexia nervosa, and must be tailored to each person's needs.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Food variety is important when establishing meal plans as well as foods that are higher in energy density, especially in carbohydrates and dietary fat, which are easier for the undernourished body to break down.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Evidence of a role for zinc supplementation during refeeding is unclear.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Dieticians work with the medical team to add dietary supplements like iron, every other day, or calcium.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Historically, practitioners have slowly increased calories at a measured pace from a starting point of around 1,200 kcal/day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] However, as understanding of the process of weight restoration has improved, an approach that favors a higher starting point and a more rapid rate of increase has become increasingly common.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In either approach, the end goal is typically in the range of 3,000 to 3,500 kcal/day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] After experiencing prolonged significant calorie deficits, people often undergo extreme hunger (hyperphagia).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Once weight is regained in both fat and muscle mass, their hunger usually returns to normalized levels.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] This process of regaining weight takes longer for fat-free/muscle mass which leads to a "fat overshoot" or "overshoot weight".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] This causes patient's body fat levels to be greater than before the disorder.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] This kind of process for hunger normalization varies between patient and could last anywhere from a few months to multiple years.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Treatment professionals tend to be conservative with refeeding in anorexic patients due to the risk of refeeding syndrome (RFS), which occurs when a malnourished person is refed too quickly for their body to be able to adapt.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Two of the most common indicators that RFS is occurring are low phosphate levels and low potassium levels.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] RFS is most likely to happen in severely or extremely underweight anorexics, as well as when medical comorbidities, such as infection or cardiac failure, are present.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In these circumstances, it is recommended to start refeeding more slowly but to build up rapidly as long as RFS does not occur.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Recommendations on energy requirements in the most medically compromised patients vary, from 5–10 kcal/kg/day to 1900 kcal/day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] This risk-averse approach can lead to underfeeding, which results in poorer outcomes for short- and long-term recovery.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Overall, pharmaceuticals have limited benefit for treating anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] However, olanzapine, an antipsychotic, has been shown to result in a modest but statistically significant increase in body weight in AN patients, in addition to a decrease in obsessive thoughts.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] While the effectiveness of antidepressants in treating anorexia has not been well established, fluoxetine, an SSRI, can also be used during treatment.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Metreleptin is undergoing research for its potential benefit in the treatment of anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] It is hypothesized that the gradual loss of body fat mass, and the ensuing low leptin levels, influence the psychological components of the disorder.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] It was shown that short-term metreleptin treatment of patients with anorexia nervosa had rapid on-set of beneficial cognitive, emotional, and behavioral effects.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Among other things, depression, drive for activity, repetitive thoughts of food, inner restlessness, and weight phobia decreased rapidly.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Whether metreleptin (or another leptin analogue) is a suitable treatment for anorexia nervosa remains to be seen.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Patients with AN may be deemed to have a lack of insight regarding the necessity of treatment, and thus may be involuntarily treated without their consent.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] AN has a high mortality and patients admitted in a severely ill state to medical units are at particularly high risk.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Diagnosis can be challenging, risk assessment may not be performed accurately, consent and the need for compulsion may not be assessed appropriately, refeeding syndrome may be missed or poorly treated and the behavioural and family problems in AN may be missed or poorly managed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Guidelines published by the Royal College of Psychiatrists recommend that medical and psychiatric experts work together in managing severely ill people with AN.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Patients involved in treatment sometimes felt that treatment focused on biological aspects of body weight and eating behaviour change rather than their perceptions or emotional state.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Patients felt that a therapist's trust in them shown by being treated as a complete person with their own capacities was significant.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Some patients defined recovery from AN in terms of reclaiming a lost identity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Additionally, access to timely treatment can be hindered by systemic challenges within the medical system.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Some individuals have reported experiencing delays in treatment, particularly when transitioning from adolescence to adulthood.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Healthcare workers involved in the treatment of anorexia reported frustration and anger to setbacks in treatment and noncompliance and were afraid of patients dying.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Some healthcare workers felt that they did not understand the treatment and that medical doctors were making decisions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] They may feel powerless to improve a patient's situation and deskilled as a result.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Healthcare workers involved in monitoring patients consumption of food felt watched themselves.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Healthcare workers would inflexibly follow process to avoid responsibility.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Healthcare workers attempted to reach balance by gradually giving patients back control avoiding feeling sole responsibility for outcomes, being mindful of their emotional state, and trying to view eating disorders as external from patients.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] AN has the highest mortality rate of any psychological disorder.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The mortality rate is 11 to 12 times greater than in the general population, and the suicide risk is 56 times higher.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Half of women with AN achieve a full recovery, while an additional 20–30% may partially recover.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Not all people with anorexia recover completely: about 20% develop anorexia nervosa as a chronic disorder.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] If anorexia nervosa is not treated, serious complications such as heart conditions and kidney failure can arise and eventually lead to death.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The average number of years from onset to remission of AN is seven for women and three for men.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] After ten to fifteen years, 70% of people no longer meet the diagnostic criteria, but many still continue to have eating-related problems.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] People who have autism recover more slowly, probably due to autism's effects on thinking patterns, such as reduced cognitive flexibility.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Alexithymia (inability to identify and describe one's own emotions) influences treatment outcome.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Recovery is also viewed on a spectrum rather than black and white.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] According to the Morgan-Russell criteria, individuals can have a good, intermediate, or poor outcome.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Even when a person is classified as having a "good" outcome, weight only has to be within 15% of average, and normal menstruation must be present in females.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The good outcome also excludes psychological health.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Recovery for people with anorexia nervosa is undeniably positive, but recovery does not mean a return to normal.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexia nervosa can have serious implications if its duration and severity are significant and if onset occurs before the completion of growth, pubertal maturation, or the attainment of peak bone mass.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Complications specific to adolescents and children with anorexia nervosa can include growth retardation, as height gain may slow and can stop completely with severe weight loss or chronic malnutrition.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In such cases, provided that growth potential is preserved, height increase can resume and reach full potential after normal intake is resumed.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Appropriate early treatment can preserve height potential, and may even help to increase it in some post-anorexic subjects, due to factors such as long-term reduced estrogen-producing adipose tissue levels compared to premorbid levels.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In some cases, especially where onset is before puberty, complications such as stunted growth and pubertal delay are usually reversible.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexia nervosa causes alterations in the female reproductive system; significant weight loss, as well as psychological stress and intense exercise, typically results in a cessation of menstruation in women who are past puberty.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In patients with anorexia nervosa, there is a reduction of the secretion of gonadotropin releasing hormone in the central nervous system which prevents ovulation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexia nervosa can also result in pubertal delay or arrest.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Both height gain and pubertal development are dependent on the release of growth hormone and gonadotropins (LH and FSH) from the pituitary gland.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Suppression of gonadotropins in people with anorexia nervosa has been documented.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Typically, growth hormone (GH) levels are high, but levels of IGF-1, the downstream hormone that should be released in response to GH are low; this indicates a state of "resistance" to GH due to chronic starvation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] IGF-1 is necessary for bone formation, and decreased levels in anorexia nervosa contribute to a loss of bone density and potentially contribute to osteopenia or osteoporosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexia nervosa can also result in reduction of peak bone mass.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Buildup of bone is greatest during adolescence, and if onset of anorexia nervosa occurs during this time and stalls puberty, low bone mass may be permanent.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Hepatic steatosis, or fatty infiltration of the liver, can also occur, and is an indicator of malnutrition in children.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Neurological disorders that may occur as complications include seizures and tremors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Wernicke encephalopathy, which results from vitamin B1 deficiency, has been reported in patients who are extremely malnourished; symptoms include confusion, problems with the muscles responsible for eye movements and abnormalities in walking gait.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Acid exposure from GERD and self-induced vomiting can cause dental problems, such as tooth enamel erosion and gum disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Delayed stomach emptying, or gastroparesis, often develops following food restriction and weight loss; the most common symptom is bloating with gas and abdominal distension, and often occurs after eating.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Other symptoms of gastroparesis include early satiety, fullness, nausea, and vomiting.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The symptoms may inhibit efforts at eating and recovery, but can be managed by limiting high-fiber foods, using liquid nutritional supplements, or using metoclopramide to increase emptying of food from the stomach.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Gastroparesis generally resolves when weight is regained.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexia nervosa increases the risk of sudden cardiac death, though the precise cause is unknown.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Cardiac complications include structural and functional changes to the heart.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Some of these cardiovascular changes are mild and are reversible with treatment, while others may be life-threatening.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Cardiac complications can include arrhythmias, abnormally slow heart beat, low blood pressure, decreased size of the heart muscle, reduced heart volume, mitral valve prolapse, myocardial fibrosis, and pericardial effusion.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Abnormalities in conduction and repolarization of the heart that can result from anorexia nervosa include QT prolongation, increased QT dispersion, conduction delays, and junctional escape rhythms.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Electrolyte abnormalities, particularly hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia, can cause anomalies in the electrical activity of the heart, and result in life-threatening arrhythmias.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Hypokalemia most commonly results in patients with anorexia when restricting is accompanied by purging (induced vomiting or laxative use).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Hypotension (low blood pressure) is common, and symptoms include fatigue and weakness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Orthostatic hypotension, a marked decrease in blood pressure when standing from a supine position, may also occur.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Symptoms include lightheadedness upon standing, weakness, and cognitive impairment, and may result in fainting or near-fainting.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Orthostasis in anorexia nervosa indicates worsening cardiac function and may indicate a need for hospitalization.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Hypotension and orthostasis generally resolve upon recovery to a normal weight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The weight loss in anorexia nervosa also causes atrophy of cardiac muscle.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] This leads to decreased ability to pump blood, a reduction in the ability to sustain exercise, a diminished ability to increase blood pressure in response to exercise, and a subjective feeling of fatigue.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Some individuals may also have a decrease in cardiac contractility.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Cardiac complications can be life-threatening, but the heart muscle generally improves with weight gain, and the heart normalizes in size over weeks to months, with recovery.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Atrophy of the heart muscle is a marker of the severity of the disease, and while it is reversible with treatment and refeeding, it is possible that it may cause permanent, microscopic changes to the heart muscle that increase the risk of sudden cardiac death.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Individuals with anorexia nervosa may experience chest pain or palpitations; these can be a result of mitral valve prolapse.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Mitral valve prolapse occurs because the size of the heart muscle decreases while the tissue of the mitral valve remains the same size.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Studies have shown rates of mitral valve prolapse of around 20 percent in those with anorexia nervosa, while the rate in the general population is estimated at 2–4 percent.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] It has been suggested that there is an association between mitral valve prolapse and sudden cardiac death, but it has not been proven to be causative, either in patients with anorexia nervosa or in the general population.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Rates of relapse after treatment range 30–72% over a period of 2–26 months, with a rate of approximately 50% in 12 months after weight restoration.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Relapse occurs in approximately a third of people in hospital, and is greatest in the first six to eighteen months after release from an institution.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] BMI or measures of body fat and leptin levels at discharge were the strongest predictors of relapse, as well as signs of eating psychopathology at discharge.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Duration of illness, age, severity, the proportion of AN binge-purge subtype, and presence of comorbidities are also contributing factors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexia is estimated to occur in 0.9% to 4.3% of women and 0.2% to 0.3% of men in Western countries at some point in their life.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] About 0.4% of young females are affected in a given year and it is estimated to occur three to ten times less commonly in males.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The cause of this disparity is not well-established but is thought to be linked to both biological and socio-cultural factors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Rates in most of the developing world are unclear.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Often it begins during the teen years or young adulthood.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Medical students are a high risk group, with an overall estimated prevalence of 10.4% globally.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The lifetime rate of atypical anorexia nervosa, a form of ED-NOS in which the person loses a significant amount of weight and is at risk for serious medical complications despite having a higher body-mass index, is much higher, at 5–12%.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] While anorexia became more commonly diagnosed during the 20th century it is unclear if this was due to an increase in its frequency or simply better diagnosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Most studies show that since at least 1970 the incidence of AN in adult women is fairly constant, while there is some indication that the incidence may have been increasing for girls aged between 14 and 20.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In non-Westernized countries, including those in Africa (excluding South Africa), eating disorders are less frequently reported and studied compared to Western countries, with available data mostly limited to case reports and isolated studies rather than prevalence investigations.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Theories to explain these lower rates of eating disorders, lower reporting, and lower research rates in these countries include the attention to effects of westernization and culture change on the prevalence of anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Athletes are often overlooked as anorexic.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Research emphasizes the importance to take athletes' diet, weight and symptoms into account when diagnosing anorexia, instead of just looking at weight and BMI.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] For athletes, ritualized activities such as weigh-ins place emphasis on gaining and losing large amounts of weight, which may promote the development of eating disorders among them.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Furthermore, the competitive mindset of elite athletes makes them especially vulnerable to anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The disorder is often largely rooted in a desire to maintain control over one's own life.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The highly competitive mindset that athletic pursuits can easily translate to the world of disordered eating.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Eating becomes "like a game" or "challenge", where the athlete is completely focused on "winning the game"; one elite swimmer with severe anorexia nervosa recalls that "it was always about losing more" and she "never wanted the game to be over".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] While anorexia nervosa is more commonly found in women, it can also affect men, with a lifetime prevalence of 0.3% in men.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] However, a lack of awareness of eating disorders in males may lead to underdiagnosis and underreporting.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Due to this limited knowledge of how anorexia nervosa is presented in males, it often takes men longer to be diagnosed and receive treatment than women.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] An additional difference is in the use of supplements to affect bodyweight, with women being more prone to using diet pills and men being more prone to using anabolic steroids.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Moreover, men who exhibit symptoms of anorexia may not meet the BMI criteria outlined in the DSM-IV due to having more muscle mass and therefore a higher bodyweight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Consequently, a subclinical diagnosis, such as *Eating Disorder Not Otherwise Specified* (ED-NOS) in the DSM-IV or *Other Specified Feeding or Eating Disorder* (OSFED) in the DSM-5, is often made instead.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Men with anorexia may also experience body dysmorphia, reporting their bodies to be twice as large than in actuality, and body dissatisfaction, especially with regard to muscularity and body composition.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Men tend to place more emphasis on a muscular build as opposed to pursuing thinness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] As in the case of women, men are more prone to develop an eating disorder if their occupation or sport emphasizes having a slim physique or lighter weight, like modeling, dancing, horse racing, wrestling, and gymnastics.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Hormonal changes may also be observed in males with anorexia nervosa, with marked changes in their serum testosterone, luteinizing hormone, and follicle stimulating hormone.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Such extreme endocrine disturbances can potentially result in infertility.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexic men are sometimes colloquially referred to as *manorexic* or as having *bigorexia*.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] An increasing trend of anorexia among the elderly, termed "Anorexia of Aging," is observed, characterized by behaviors similar to those seen in typical anorexia nervosa but often accompanied by excessive laxative use.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Most geriatric anorexia patients limit their food intake to dairy or grains, whereas an adolescent anorexic has a more general limitation.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] This eating disorder that affects older adults has two types – early onset and late onset.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Early onset refers to a recurrence of anorexia in late life in an individual who experienced the disease during their youth.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Late onset describes instances where the eating disorder begins for the first time late in life.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The stimulus for anorexia in elderly patients is typically a loss of control over their lives, which can be brought on by many events, including moving into an assisted living facility.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] This is also a time when most older individuals experience a rise in conflict with family members, such as limitations on driving or limitations on personal freedom, which increases the likelihood of an issue with anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] There can be physical issues in the elderly that leads to anorexia of aging, including a decline in chewing ability, a decline in taste and smell, and a decrease in appetite.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Psychological reasons for the elderly to develop anorexia can include depression and bereavement, and even an indirect attempt at suicide.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] There are also common comorbid psychiatric conditions with aging anorexics, including major depression, anxiety disorder, obsessive compulsive disorder, bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, and dementia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The signs and symptoms that go along with anorexia of aging are similar to what is observed in adolescent anorexia, including sudden weight loss, unexplained hair loss or dental problems, and a desire to eat alone.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] There are also several medical conditions that can result from anorexia in the elderly.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] An increased risk of illness and death can be a result of anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] There is also a decline in muscle and bone mass as a result of a reduction in protein intake during anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Another result of anorexia in the aging population is irreparable damage to kidneys, heart or colon and an imbalance of electrolytes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Many assessments are available to diagnose anorexia in the aging community.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] These assessments include the Simplified Nutritional Assessment Questionnaire (SNAQ) and Functional Assessment of Anorexia/Cachexia Therapy (FAACT).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Specific to the geriatric populace, the interRAI system identifies detrimental conditions in assisted living facilities and nursing homes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Even a simple screening for nutritional insufficiencies such as low levels of important vitamins, can help to identify someone who has anorexia of aging.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Anorexia in the elderly should be identified by the retirement communities but is often overlooked, especially in patients with dementia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Some studies report that malnutrition is prevalent in nursing homes, with up to 58% of residents suffering from it, which can lead to the difficulty of identifying anorexia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] One of the challenges with assisted living facilities is that they often serve bland, monotonous food, which lessens residents' desire to eat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The treatment for anorexia of aging is undifferentiated as anorexia for any other age group.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Some of the treatment options include outpatient and inpatient facilities, antidepressant medication and behavioral therapy such as meal observation and discussing eating habits.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The history of anorexia nervosa begins with descriptions of religious fasting dating from the Hellenistic era and continuing into the medieval period.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The medieval practice of self-starvation by women, including some young women, in the name of religious piety and purity is sometimes referred to as *anorexia mirabilis.* The earliest medical descriptions of anorexic illnesses are generally credited to English physician Richard Morton in 1689.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Etymologically, *anorexia* is a term of Greek origin: *an-* (ἀν-, prefix denoting negation) and *orexis* (ὄρεξις, "appetite"), translating literally to "a loss of appetite".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In and of itself, this term does not have a harmful connotation, e.g., *exercise-induced anorexia* simply means that hunger is naturally suppressed during and after sufficiently intense exercise sessions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] It is the adjective *nervosa* that indicates the functional and non-organic nature of the disorder, but this adjective is also often omitted when the context is clear.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Despite the literal translation of anorexia, the feeling of hunger in anorexia nervosa is frequently present and the pathological control of this instinct is a source of satisfaction for the patients.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] The term "anorexia nervosa" was coined in 1873 by Sir William Gull, one of Queen Victoria's personal physicians.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Gull published a seminal paper providing a number of detailed case descriptions of patients with anorexia nervosa.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In the same year, French physician Ernest-Charles Lasègue similarly published details of a number of cases in a paper entitled *De l'Anorexie hystérique*.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] In the late 19th century anorexia nervosa became widely accepted by the medical profession as a recognized condition, with mentions in the medical literature notably arising from the Salpêtrière clinic in Paris by physicians such as Jean-Martin Charcot.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Awareness of the condition was largely limited to the medical profession until the latter part of the 20th century, when German-American psychoanalyst Hilde Bruch published *The Golden Cage: the Enigma of Anorexia Nervosa* in 1978.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] Despite major advances in neuroscience, Bruch's theories tend to dominate popular thinking.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anorexia-p02] A further important event was the death of the popular singer and drummer Karen Carpenter in 1983, which prompted widespread ongoing media coverage of eating disorders.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Weight loss drugs have been developed since the early twentieth century, and many have been banned or withdrawn from the market due to adverse effects, including deaths; other drugs proved ineffective.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Although many earlier drugs were stimulants such as amphetamines, in the early 2020s, GLP-1 receptor agonists became popular for weight loss.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] As of 2023, the medications liraglutide, naltrexone/bupropion, orlistat, semaglutide, tirzepatide and phentermine/topiramate are approved by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for weight management in combination with reduced-calorie diet and increased physical activity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Medications to treat obesity may be considered in those with a body mass index above 30, or above 27 with obesity related complications (such as hypertension, hyperlipidemia, cardiovascular disease, or obstructive sleep apnea).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] As of 2022, no medication has been shown to be as effective at long-term weight reduction as bariatric surgery.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] The first described attempts at producing weight loss are those of Soranus of Ephesus, a Greek physician, in the second century AD.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] He prescribed elixirs of laxatives and purgatives, as well as heat, massage, and exercise.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] This remained the mainstay of treatment for well over a thousand years.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] It was not until the 1920s and 1930s that new treatments began to appear.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Based on its effectiveness for hypothyroidism, thyroid hormone became a popular treatment for obesity in euthyroid people.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] It had a modest effect but produced the symptoms of hyperthyroidism as a side effect, such as palpitations and difficulty sleeping.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] 2,4-Dinitrophenol (DNP) was introduced in 1933; this worked by uncoupling the biological process of oxidative phosphorylation in mitochondria, causing them to produce heat instead of ATP.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Overdose caused fatal hyperthermia and DNP also caused cataracts in some users.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] After the passage of the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act in 1938, the FDA banned DNP for human consumption.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Amphetamines (marketed as Benzedrine) became popular for weight loss during the late 1930s.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] They worked primarily by suppressing appetite, and had other beneficial effects such as increased alertness.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Use of amphetamines increased over the subsequent decades, including Obetrol and culminating in the "rainbow diet pill" regime.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] This was a combination of multiple pills, all thought to help with weight loss, taken throughout the day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Typical regimens included stimulants, such as amphetamines, as well as thyroid hormone, diuretics, digitalis, laxatives, and often a barbiturate to suppress the side effects of the stimulants.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] In 1967/1968 a number of deaths attributed to diet pills triggered a Senate investigation and the gradual implementation of greater restrictions on the market.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] While rainbow diet pills were banned in the US in the late 1960s, they reappeared in South America and Europe in the 1980s.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] In 1959, phentermine had been FDA approved and fenfluramine in 1973.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] In the early 1990s two studies found that a combination of the drugs was more effective than either on its own; *fen-phen* became popular in the United States and had more than 18 million prescriptions in 1996.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Evidence mounted that the combination could cause valvular heart disease in up to 30 percent of those who had taken it, leading to withdrawal of fen-phen and dexfenfluramine from the market in September 1997.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] In the early 2020s, GLP-1 receptor agonists such as semaglutide (Ozempic, Wegovy) or tirzepatide (Zepbound) became popular for weight loss because they are more effective than earlier drugs, causing a shortage for patients prescribed these medications for type 2 diabetes, their original indication.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] After the FDA approved semaglutide and tirzepatide for chronic weight management, GLP-1 medications became available through various virtual weight loss programs.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] GLP-1 receptor agonists are associated with reduced riks of cardiovascular events (such as heart attack and stroke) in adults with obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] The United States Food and Drug Administration and the European Medicines Agency have approved weight loss medications for adults with either a body-mass index (BMI) of at least 30, or a body-mass index of at least 27 with at least one weight-related comorbidity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] This patient population is considered to have sufficiently high baseline health risks to justify the use of anti-obesity medication.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] The American Academy of Pediatrics had not previously supported the use of weight loss medication in adolescents but issued new guidelines in 2023, which recommend considering the use of weight loss medication in some overweight children aged 12 or older.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] The European Medicines Agency has approved semaglutide for children aged 12 or older who have a BMI in the 95 percentile for their age and a weight of at least 60 kilograms (130 lb).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] However, GLP-1 agonists may not be cost effective in this population.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approves anti-obesity medications as an adjunctive therapy to diet and exercise for people for whom lifestyle changes do not result in sufficient weight loss.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] In the United States, semaglutide (Wegovy) is approved by the FDA for chronic weight management.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] The FDA guidelines say that a therapy may be approved if it results in weight loss that is statistically significant greater than placebo and generally at least five percent of body weight over six months that comes predominantly from fat mass.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Some other prescription weight loss medications are stimulants, which are recommended only for short-term use, and thus are of limited usefulness for patients who may need to reduce weight over months or years.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] As of 2022, there is no pathway for approval for drugs that reduce fat mass without 5 percent overall weight loss, even if they significantly improve metabolic health; neither is there one for drugs that help patients maintain weight loss although this can be more challenging than losing weight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] As of 2022, no medication has been discovered that would equal the effectiveness of bariatric surgery for long-term weight loss and improved health outcomes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Some anti-obesity medications can have severe, even lethal side effects, fen-phen being a famous example.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Fen-phen was reported through the FDA to cause abnormal echocardiograms, heart valve problems, and rare valvular diseases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Out of 25 anti-obesity medications withdrawn from the market between 1964 and 2009, 23 acted by altering the functions of chemical neurotransmitters in the brain.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] The most common side effects of these drugs that led to withdrawals were mental disturbances, cardiac side effects, and drug abuse or drug dependence.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Deaths were associated with seven products.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Ephedra was removed from the US market in 2004 over concerns that it raises blood pressure and could lead to strokes and death.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] Weight regain is common upon discontinuation of weight loss medications, and long-term therapy may sometimes be required for sustained weight loss.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] After stopping treatment with GLP-1 agonists such as semaglutide, liraglutide and tirzepatide, people regain on average more than half (50–70%) of the lost weight within 1 year.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/anti-obesity-medication] People return to their previous weight within a year and a half after stopping anti-obesity medications.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] Atherosclerosis is the primary cause of coronary artery disease (CAD) and stroke, with multiple genetic and environmental contributions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] Genetic-epidemiologic studies have identified many genetic and non-genetic risk factors for CAD.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] However, such studies indicate that family history is the most significant independent risk factor.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] The signs and symptoms of arteriosclerosis depend on the vessel affected by the disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] If affecting cerebral or ophthalmic vessels, as in cerebrovascular accidents or transient ischemic attacks, signs and symptoms may include sudden weakness, facial or lower limb numbness, confusion, difficulty understanding speech, and problems seeing.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] If affecting coronary vessels, as in coronary artery disease (including acute coronary syndrome), signs and symptoms may include chest pain.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] The lesions of arteriosclerosis begin when the intima (the innermost layer of a blood vessel wall) of an artery starts to fill up with the deposition of cellular wastes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] As these develop, they can take different forms of arteriosclerosis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] All are linked through common features such as the stiffening of arterial vessels, thickening of arterial walls and the degenerative nature of the disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] Diagnosis of an individual suspected of having arteriosclerosis can be based on a physical exam, blood test, EKG and the results of these tests (among other exams).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] Treatment is often in the form of preventive measures or prophylaxis.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] Lifestyle changes are also advised, such as increasing exercise, stopping smoking, and moderating alcohol intake.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] In 2008, the US had an estimate of 16 million cases of atherosclerotic heart disease and 5.8 million strokes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] Cardiovascular diseases that were caused by arteriosclerosis also caused almost 812,000 deaths in 2008, more than any other cause, including cancer.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] About 1.2 million Americans are predicted to have a heart attack each year.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] The diagnostics and clinical implications of this disease were not recognized until the 20th century.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] Many cases have been observed and recorded, and Jean Lobstein coined the term *arteriosclerosis* while he was analyzing the composition of calcified arterial lesions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/arteriosclerosis] The name "arteriosclerosis" is derived the Greek words ἀρτηρία (*artēría*, artery) and σκληρωτικός (*sklērōtikós*, hardened).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food has been criticized for negative health effects, animal cruelty, cases of worker exploitation, children-targeted marketing and claims of cultural degradation via shifts in people's eating patterns away from traditional foods.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food chains have come under fire from consumer groups, such as the Center for Science in the Public Interest, a longtime fast food critic over issues such as caloric content, trans fats and portion sizes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Social scientists have highlighted how the prominence of fast food narratives in popular urban legends suggests that modern consumers have an ambivalent relationship (characterized by guilt) with fast food, particularly in relation to children.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Some of these concerns have helped give rise to the slow food and local food movements.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] These movements seek to promote local cuisines and ingredients, and directly oppose laws and habits that encourage fast food choices.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Proponents of the slow food movement try to educate consumers about what its members consider the environmental, nutritional, and taste benefits of fresh, local foods.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food often contains significant amounts of mayonnaise, cheese, salt, fried meat, and oil.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] These ingredients are typically high in calories and fat, contributing to their energy-dense nature (Schlosser).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Consuming excessive amounts of such foods can lead to an unbalanced diet.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Health experts, including dieticians, generally recommend a balanced diet that includes adequate proteins, vitamins, and minerals, while limiting excessive intake of fats and carbohydrates.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The overconsumption of fast food has been associated with various health problems, including obesity and cardiovascular diseases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Additionally, research indicates that frequent consumption of fast food may negatively impact appetite regulation and respiratory system function., and central nervous system function (Schlosser).
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In a cross-sectional data study of more than 100,000 adolescents in 32 countries (including low-, middle-, and high-income countries), it was found that fast food is associated with an increase in suicide attempts.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] According to the Massachusetts Medical Society Committee, fast foods are commonly high in fat content, and studies have found associations between fast food intake and increased body mass index (BMI) and weight gain.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In particular, many fast foods are high in saturated fats, which are widely held to be a risk factor in heart disease.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In 2010, heart disease was the number 1 ranking cause of death.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] A 2006 study fed monkeys a diet with a similar level of trans fats as that of a person who ate fast food frequently.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Both diets contained the same overall number of calories.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] It was found that the monkeys who consumed higher levels of trans fat developed more abdominal fat than those fed a diet rich in unsaturated fats.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] They also developed signs of insulin resistance, an early indicator of diabetes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] After six years on the diet, the trans fat fed monkeys had gained 7.2% of their body weight, compared to just 1.8% in the unsaturated fat group.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] A five-year study conducted in Singapore showed that frequent fast food consumers (more than twice a week) had a significant increased risk of developing type 2 diabetes and an increased risk of death from coronary heart disease, when compared to non-consumers.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The American Heart Association recommends consumption of about 16 grams of saturated fats a day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The director of the obesity program for the Children's Hospital Boston, David Ludwig, says that "fast food consumption has been shown to increase caloric intake, promote weight gain, and elevate risk for diabetes".
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The link between eating fast food and developing diabetes is a major cause for alarm.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Consuming fast food on a daily basis has been linked to an increased risk of acquiring type 2 diabetes.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Insulin resistance and impaired glucose metabolism are common health consequences of a diet heavy in processed carbs, bad fats, and added sweets found in fast food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Type 2 diabetes is a chronic, disabling disease with serious health effects, and its development is influenced by the aforementioned risk factors.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Excessive calories are another issue with fast food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Desalvo, from "Fast Food, Race/Ethnicity, and Income: A Geographic Analysis", 2004, referring to a U.S.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Department of Agriculture sponsored study, "the percentage of calories which can be attributed to fast-food consumption has increased from 3% to 12% of the total calories consumed in the United States from 1978 to 1995.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In 1995, "away-from-home" foods provided 34% of total caloric intake and 38% of total fat intake compared to 18% for both categories in 1977–1978." A regular meal at McDonald's consists of a Big Mac, large fries, and a large Coca-Cola drink amounting to 1,430 calories.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] However, besides fast food consumption, there are many other reasons for overweight among children while they are growing, including sex development, "hormonal changes", and social interactions.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] At those moments young people can feel depressed, which may lead to increase or decrease in appetite.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In fact, increased hunger may lead to obesity in some cases.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The fast food chain D'Lites, founded in 1978, specialized in lower-calorie dishes and healthier alternatives such as salads.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] It filed for bankruptcy in 1987 as other fast food chains began offering healthier options.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] McDonald's has been attempting to offer healthier options besides salads.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] They have incorporated fruit and milk as options of Happy Meals and have promoted healthier ads and packaging for children.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The Alliance for a Healthier Generation has set a standard in hopes of pressuring fast food companies to make recommended healthier adjustments.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food often comes in wrappers coated with polyfluoroalkyl phosphate esters (PAPs) to prevent grease from leaking through them.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] These compounds are able to migrate from the wrappers into the packaged food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Upon ingestion, PAPs are subsequently biotransformed into perfluorinated carboxylic acids (PFCAs), compounds which have long attracted attention due to their detrimental health effects in rodents and their unusually long half-lives in humans.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] On average, nearly one-third of U.S. children aged 4 to 19 eat fast food every day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Over the course of a year this is likely to result in a child gaining six extra pounds in weight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In a research experiment published in *Pediatrics*, 6,212 children and adolescents aged 4 to 19 were examined to extrapolate some information about fast food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Upon interviewing the participants in the experiment, it was reported that on any given day 30.3% of the total sample had eaten fast food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast-food consumption was prevalent in both males and females, in all racial/ethnic groups, and in all regions of the country.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Additionally, in the study children who ate fast food, compared to those who did not, tended to consume more total fat, carbohydrates, and sugar-sweetened beverages.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Children who ate fast food also tended to eat less fiber, milk, fruits, and non-starchy vegetables.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] After reviewing these test results, the researchers concluded that consumption of fast food by children seems to have a negative effect on an individual's diet, in ways that could significantly increase the risk of obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Due to having reduced cognitive defenses against marketing, children may be more susceptible to fast food advertisements, and consequently have a higher risk of becoming obese.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food is only a minuscule factor that contributes to childhood obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] A study conducted by researchers at The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill's Gillings School of Global Public Health showed that poor diet and obesity as an overall factor are the leading causes of rising obesity rates in children.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] "While reducing fast-food intake is important, the rest of a child's diet should not be overlooked", said Jennifer Poti, co-author and doctoral candidate in the university's Department of Nutrition.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Contrary evidence has been documented that questions the correlation of a fast food diet and obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] A 2014 People Magazine article recounts the experience, with a sample size of one, of John Cisna, a science teacher at Colo-NESCO High School, who ate a fast food diet for 90 days.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] At the end of 90 days he had lost 37 pounds and his cholesterol level went from 249 to 170.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Cisna kept to a strict 2,000 calorie limit a day and walked 45 minutes a day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Harley Pasternak, a celebrity trainer and nutrition expert, supports Cisna's experiment by saying, "While I don't think it's a great idea to eat too much fast food...
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food, while far from healthy, doesn't make people gain weight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Eating too much fast food too often is what can make you gain weight—the same way eating too much of anything can pack on the pounds." A cross-sectional study in China shows that the relationship between BMI and times per week fast food consumption was not significant.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Jared Fogle's drastic weight loss on a Subway diet, which is considered a fast food chain, is another case that poses a fair debate against the idea that the culprit of obesity is fast food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fogle dropped 235 pounds by consuming Subway sandwiches for lunch and dinner daily.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] With no cheese or mayonnaise, the calories of both sandwiches totaled less than 1,000 calories in a day.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food labels without the calorie amount increase the risks of obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Mclnerney et al. is examined the impact of fast food labeling on college students' weight loss.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In the study the students required to label the calories of fast foods in the items' lists.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The results showed positive effects on the significance of weight loss among college students.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Thus, fast food restaurants need to post the caloric content of their products to inform the consumers about their food choices in order to prevent obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] A 2012, estimated report by the US Federal Trade Commission revealed a $7.9 billion marketing expenditure difference between expenditure on marketing to all audiences and expenditure on marketing strictly to children and adolescents.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] According to this report, Fast food industries spent approximately $9.7 billion on marketing food and beverages to the general audience while they spent only $1.8 billion on marketing to children and adolescents.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Spokespeople for the fast food industry claim that there are no good or bad foods, but instead there are good or bad diets.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The industry has defended itself by placing the burden of healthy eating on the consumer, who freely chooses to consume their product outside of what nutritional recommendations allow.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Many fast food restaurants added labels to their menus by listing the nutritional information below each item.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The intent was to inform consumers of the caloric and nutritional content of the food being served there and result in directing consumers to the healthier options available.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] However, reports do not display any significant drop in sales at sandwich or burger locations which highlights no change in consumer behavior even after food was labeled.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food is also affordable on people's incomes and expenses relating to the regions they live.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] "Healthy foods including whole-grain products, low-fat dairy foods, and fresh fruits and vegetables may be less available, and relatively costlier, in poor and minority neighborhoods." So, fast food stores are located in the areas where the demand by the population is high.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Some other studies show that eating fast food is not dependent on a person's income.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Researchers found that an amount of fast food consumed does not correlate with a person's income level.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The article "Wealth doesn't equal health Wealth: Fast food consequences not just for poor", discusses the issue: not all rich people are healthy food consumers, nor do they consume fast food less frequently than poor people.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Additionally, fast food customers work harder and longer than those who do not eat fast food daily.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In this 12-hour observational study, about 34% of meals purchased were take-away, meals that were excluded from the study, and 65% represented the unhealthy eat-in meals while the remaining 1% represented the healthy meals purchased.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Restrained eating, or excessive consumption of fast food and other unhealthy foods high in sugar and sodium, is a category of different eating habits derived from results of a cross-sectional study in 2014.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] This study depicted a prominent association between restrained eating and nurses working overnight shifts and those who are under high stress.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fruits and vegetables were reported as the least likely to be consumed under stress.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] About 395 nurses participated in this study.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] All these nurses were employees of two major hospitals in the capital city, Riyadh, of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The research gathered from a nationwide study in China strictly concentrated on the link between fast food consumption and the growing obesity epidemic in children, ranging from ages 6–18.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Although end results were not completely inconclusive, there was no significant relationship found between the two.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The variables taken into consideration to support and narrow the study showed that fast food consumption rates increased with the presence of any of the following variables: low-income households, peer influence, geographical location, pocket money and independence.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food consumption rates escalated when older children were surveyed whilst consumption rates for younger children appeared normal.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Also, western fast food was preferred by children of all ages because they associated western fast food with high quality food.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] "The McLawsuit" was a group of overweight children that filed a class action lawsuit against McDonald's seeking compensation for obesity related reasons.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR) Effect is a phrase used to judge a category based on judgments from other similar categories or is in relation to them.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] To put it in terms of the fast food industry, a customer who had a bad experience at a McDonald's would associate that experience with other McDonald's, casting a per-conspired image in their mind of how all other McDonald's are.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Many fast food employees are adults who earn minimum wage, which in the United States is around $7.25 for every hour.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Around 60% of fast food workers are 25 years and older.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Many employees have protested to raise the minimum wage.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] On 5 December 2013, protesters from 100 cities in the United States held demonstrations for a $15 hourly wage.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] This protest was one of a series of strikes that began 2012, in New York City, protesting against low wages.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In the largest increase in decades, fast food workers have seen a 10% increase in pay since 2020.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] There has been a study over employee wages at the fast food companies, the study suggests the fast food industry needs to increase an hourly payment from "7.25 to 10.25" for the beginners of the job.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Besides, they recommend to rise that to 5 dollars after few years of experience.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] From that it is clear to understand that how increased minimum wages has its effects on employees services, life style, and well-being.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Because workers start to work better when their life style changes as well as their payments.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The 2019 COVID-19 pandemic has created many challenges for businesses to stay afloat.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The pandemic led to many business cutting hours for minimum wage workers, which led workers to seek new employment opportunities.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food workers continue to face hostile work environments for those who choose to stay.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] They are already in a low paying job and need to go to work so they continue show up even if they show any symptoms due to lack of coverage and legislation that only support COVID-19 related illnesses.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] With two thirds of front line workers being women with a minor child at home, the only option is to show up for work.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Social distancing is not always an option in fast food restaurants due to limited space.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Fast food workers were not always provided with proper PPE, one worker even cited utilizing the same mask for up to a week at a time.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Both of these variables contributed to fast food workers being at a higher risk for contracting the virus.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The pandemic intensified the mental health issues that fast-food workers had already faced.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] On top of the known mental health issues, they now had a fear of losing their jobs, contracting COVID-19 and spreading the virus to others.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The fast food workers have said they have dealt with being sexually harassed and mentally abused.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] More than 60% of workers have experienced some form of abuse since the pandemic.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] A 2011 study of litter in the San Francisco Bay Area by Clean Water Action found that nearly half of the litter present on the streets was fast food packaging.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The EPA states that only a tiny proportion of the plastic waste generated by the fast food industry is recycled.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The use of disposable tableware shifts costs from in-house employment to the municipal waste stream.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] By convincing consumers to bus disposable tableware, mostly in the 1960-1975 time period, formula fast food restaurants were able to gain competitive advantage over full-service lunch counter operations, despite the additional cost of the disposable items.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Some attempts at discouraging this have been made, but the custom of busing disposable items is still widespread.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Other measures include "Carryout Bag" laws and restrictions on formula restaurants.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In 2013, McDonald's and Dunkin' Brands publicly pledged to transition out of their use of foam hot beverage cups.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] McDonald's has replaced foam with paper cups, but Dunkin' has not initiated transition.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The use of foam cups can still be seen at Chick-fil-A, Burger King, and KFC.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Chipotle uses aluminum meal lids that are made from 95% recycled material, but they do not have postconsumer recycling, so the lids that are left on-site are landfilled.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In 2015, a gruesome video clip of a T&S farm in Dukedom, Tennessee, was released by animal rights activists, where workers were caught abusing chickens.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Tyson Foods, the company which delivers chicken nuggets to the fast food giant McDonald's, cancelled their contract with the farm stating "animal well-being" is their utmost priority.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] McDonald's supported Tyson Foods' decision and described the workers actions as unacceptable.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In 2013, McDonald's announced that they would include fruits and vegetables in their menu combinations.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] In 2016 the company replaced the high-fructose corn syrup in its hamburger buns with sugar and removed antibiotics that are "important to human medicine" from its chicken.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] They also removed artificial preservatives from their cooking oil, pork sausage patties, eggs served on the breakfast menu, and Chicken McNuggets.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The skin, safflower oil and citric acid from the McNuggets was also replaced with pea starch, rice starch and powdered lemon juice.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Many fast food chains have reduced their material usage by "lightweighting", or reducing material in a package by weight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] McDonald's made over 10 reduction in packaging weight in 2012, such as a 48% reduction in the chicken sandwich paperboard carton, and an 18–28% reduction in its plastic cold cups.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Starbucks has reduced their water bottle weight by 20% and cold cups by 15%.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Over 160 companies in the food sector announced that they are planning to shift to eggs from only cage-free hens, most by the year 2025 .
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] The list includes McDonald's, Dunkin' Donuts, Carl's Jr., Burger King, Denny's, Jack in the Box, Quiznos, Shake Shack, Starbucks, Sonic, Taco Bell, Wendy's, White Castle, and Subway, among others.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] A study of students who live within a half mile from fast food locations have been reported to consume fewer amounts of fruit and vegetables, consume more soda, and are more likely to be overweight.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] More other studies show that the exposure to poor-quality food environments has important effects on adolescent eating patterns and obesity.
[src:criticism-of-fast-food/criticism-of-fast-food] Therefore, it seems that policy interventions limiting the proximity of fast-food restaurants to schools could help reduce adolescent obesity.
